<main class="content" id="main-content">
<div class="unit-block active" id="unit-0"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 1 of 36 · A1 Part 1</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">🌱 Part 1 — Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Greetings &amp; Introductions</div><div class="unit-desc">Absolute zero. Students learn to say hello, introduce themselves, ask basic questions and say goodbye. Every phrase learned here is the bedrock of the entire A1 level and is recycled in every unit that follows.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:5%"></div></div></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Meeting People</div><div class="lesson-sub">Greetings · Farewells · Politeness · Basic responses</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Hello / Hi / Hey</div><div class="vd">informal greeting</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Good morning / Good afternoon / Good evening</div><div class="vd">time-based greetings</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Goodbye / Bye / See you soon</div><div class="vd">farewells</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">My name is… / I'm…</div><div class="vd">self-introduction</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What's your name?</div><div class="vd">asking name</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Nice to meet you / Pleased to meet you</div><div class="vd">first meeting</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How are you? / How do you do?</div><div class="vd">wellbeing question</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Fine / Very well / Not bad / Great</div><div class="vd">wellbeing answers</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Please / Thank you / You're welcome</div><div class="vd">politeness</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Sorry / Excuse me / Pardon?</div><div class="vd">apology / attention</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Yes / No / OK / Of course</div><div class="vd">basic responses</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I don't understand / Can you repeat that?</div><div class="vd">comprehension phrases</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Greeting Circle</div><div class="ad">Students stand in a circle. Each greets the next person differently — no two consecutive students may use the same greeting. Forces full use of the vocabulary immediately.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Situation Cards</div><div class="ad">Cards describe scenarios (morning at work / meeting a new colleague / saying goodbye to a friend). Students choose the right phrase for each.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Polite or Impolite?</div><div class="ad">Teacher says phrases with and without please/sorry. Students rate polite (👍) or impolite (👎) and correct the impolite ones.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — To Be: am / is / are</div><div class="lesson-sub">Positive · Negative · Yes/No questions · Short answers · Contractions</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Subject Pronouns + To Be — Positive</div><div class=ge>The verb changes depending on the subject. Use contractions from the very first lesson — they are the natural spoken form.</div><div class="ex">I am Maria. → I'm Maria.</div><div class="ex">You are from France. → You're from France.</div><div class="ex">He is a student. / She is a teacher. / It is a big school.</div><div class="ex">We are in class. / They are from Greece. / You are all students.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Negative — To Be + not</div><div class=ge>Two contracted forms exist for some pronouns. Both are correct and should be learned.</div><div class="ex">I am not Russian. → I'm not Russian. (only one contracted form)</div><div class="ex">She is not a doctor. → She isn't a doctor. / She's not a doctor.</div><div class="ex">They are not from England. → They aren't from England.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Yes/No Questions — invert subject and verb</div><div class=ge>Never add do/does to to be questions. This is the most common error at A1.</div><div class="ex">Are you from England? — Yes, I am. / No, I'm not.</div><div class="ex">Is he a student? — Yes, he is. / No, he isn't.</div><div class="ex">Are they teachers? — Yes, they are. / No, they aren't.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Is or Are? Rapid Fire</div><div class="ad">Teacher points at individuals or groups. Students must produce the correct form instantly: is (singular) or are (plural/you).</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Correct the Robot</div><div class="ad">Teacher speaks as a "robot" making to be errors. Students correct every mistake.</div><div class=ap>"I is from France." → You are not a robot! He IS from France! / "They am students." → They ARE students!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Introduce Yourself</div><div class="lesson-sub">All L1 vocabulary + am/is/are · Real conversation from minute one</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">Hello/Goodbye</span><span class="vr">My name is…</span><span class="vr">I'm from…</span><span class="vr">Nice to meet you</span><span class="vr">How are you?</span><span class="vr">Fine/Very well</span><span class="vr">am/is/are</span><span class="vr">isn't/aren't</span><span class="vr">Yes/No short answers</span><span class="vr">I don't understand</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Mingle: Find Someone Who…</div><div class="ad">Students walk around greeting each other and finding classmates who match prompts. Full sentences mandatory.</div><div class=ap>Find someone who is from France. / Find someone whose name starts with M. / Find someone who is a student. → Are you from France? — Yes, I am! / No, I'm not. I'm from Italy. — Nice to meet you! I'm Ana.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Hot Seat: Guess the Country</div><div class="ad">Student in hot seat thinks of a country. Class asks yes/no questions using to be only.</div><div class=ap>Are you from Europe? — Yes, I am. / Is it a small country? — No, it isn't. / Are you from Russia? — Yes, I am!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Chain Introduction</div><div class="ad">A introduces themselves. B repeats A's info + introduces themselves. C repeats both + adds their own. Full he/she/they practice of to be.</div><div class=ap>This is Ana. She's from Greece. She's a teacher. I'm Marco. I'm from Italy. I'm a student.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With & Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Life before this language · Full Unit 1 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">⚖️ MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Why are you learning this language — and what was your life like without it?</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Hello! My name is… I am from… I am a…" — students greet each other as if for the first time. Every phrase from L1 must appear.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Why are you here? What is your life like without this language? Students answer: "English is important for my job. I am a teacher from Italy. Without English I am lost in meetings!"</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher writes student sentences on the board. Highlights correct am/is/are. Corrects third-person is/isn't errors live — most common mistake.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge (1 min):</strong> "Talk about yourself — name, country, age, why you are here. Don't stop." Teacher counts correct uses of to be.</span></div><div class="rnote">📌 All Unit 1 vocabulary active. Teacher marks any words not yet used in speech for recycling in Unit 2.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 1 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Vocabulary · Grammar · Speaking · Writing</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Match 5 greetings to situations: morning / first meeting / goodbye / apology / not understanding</div><div class=ei>Write the correct response to: "How are you?" / "Nice to meet you!" / "Thank you!"</div><div class=ei>Translate 5 politeness phrases into English</div><div class=ei>Choose: Sorry / Excuse me / Pardon — for 3 different situations</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences with am / is / are / isn't / aren't</div><div class=ei>Turn 3 statements into yes/no questions using to be</div><div class=ei>Write 3 short answers: Yes, I ___ / No, she ___ / Yes, they ___</div><div class=ei>Correct 4 errors — all to be mistakes: wrong pronoun, wrong form, missing contraction</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min self-introduction: name, country, age, job/study, one sentence about yourself</div><div class=ei>Answer 3 yes/no questions from the teacher using full short answers</div><div class=ei>Greet and introduce a partner to the class using he/she is</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write 5–6 sentences about yourself. Must include: am (×1) · is (×2) · are (×1) · isn't or aren't (×1) · Nice to meet you.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" disabled>← Start</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(1)">Unit 2 →</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-1"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 2 of 36 · A1 Part 1</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">🌱 Part 1 — Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Numbers &amp; Personal Info</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to give and ask for personal information: age, phone number, address, email. Numbers 1–100 become essential tools. The alphabet is introduced for spelling names and emails.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:9%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">♻️&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> am/is/are · Yes/No questions · short answers · subject pronouns · greetings · all Unit 1 vocabulary active in every exercise.</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Numbers &amp; Personal Information</div><div class="lesson-sub">Numbers 1–100 · Age · Phone · Address · Alphabet basics</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Unit 1</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">Hello/Goodbye</span><span class="vr">I'm from…</span><span class="vr">am/is/are</span><span class="vr">Nice to meet you</span><span class="vr">What's your name?</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">one – ten</div><div class="vd">numbers 1–10</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">eleven – twenty</div><div class="vd">numbers 11–20</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">twenty-one – one hundred</div><div class="vd">numbers 21–100</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How old are you? / I am … years old</div><div class="vd">asking/giving age</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What is your phone number?</div><div class="vd">asking for number</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Where do you live?</div><div class="vd">asking address</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I live in… / My address is…</div><div class="vd">giving location</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What is your email?</div><div class="vd">digital contact</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">A B C … Z</div><div class="vd">English alphabet — spelling names</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How do you spell…?</div><div class="vd">spelling question</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">first / second / third / fourth … tenth</div><div class="vd">ordinal numbers 1–10</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">zero / oh</div><div class="vd">number zero (phone numbers)</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Number Tennis</div><div class="ad">Students volley numbers back and forth in pairs — one counts up, one counts down. Then switch to odds only, evens only.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spell Your Name</div><div class="ad">Students spell their name aloud. Others write it. Checks alphabet + listening + numbers (name length).</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Find Someone Whose…</div><div class="ad">Mingle using to be (U1) + new number vocab.</div><div class=ap>"Is your phone number long? How old are you? Are you 30? — No, I'm not. I'm 28." — Yes, I am! — Nice to meet you!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — To Be: Wh- Questions · Article a/an · Plural Nouns</div><div class="lesson-sub">What / Where / How old · a/an before singular nouns · -s/-es plurals</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Unit 1</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are</span><span class="vr">subject pronouns</span><span class="vr">Yes/No questions</span><span class="vr">short answers</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Wh- Questions with To Be</div><div class=ge>Word order: Wh- word + am/is/are + subject. Never use do/does — these are to be questions.</div><div class="ex">What is your name? → What's your name?</div><div class="ex">Where are you from? / Where is he from?</div><div class="ex">How old are you? — I am 25. / How old is she? — She is 30.</div><div class="ex">What is your phone number? / What is your email address?</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Article: a / an</div><div class=ge>Use a before consonant sounds. Use an before vowel sounds. Only with singular countable nouns.</div><div class="ex">I am a student. / She is a teacher. / He is an engineer.</div><div class="ex">It is a big city. / It is an old building.</div><div class="ex">I have a phone number. / She has an email address.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Plural Nouns — -s / -es / irregular</div><div class=ge>Most nouns add -s. Nouns ending in -s/-sh/-ch/-x add -es. Some are irregular.</div><div class="ex">student → students / teacher → teachers / number → numbers</div><div class="ex">address → addresses / class → classes</div><div class="ex">person → people / child → children (preview — formally taught in Unit 3)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Question Machine</div><div class="ad">Students write answers about themselves. Partner writes the questions. Then check — every question must use to be correctly.</div><div class=ap>"I am 27." → How old are you? / "I am from Italy." → Where are you from?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">a or an?</div><div class="ad">Rapid-fire: teacher says a noun, students say "a ___" or "an ___" instantly. Includes all jobs and nationalities they'll need in future units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Personal Information Exchange</div><div class="lesson-sub">All Units 1+2 active · Wh- questions · Numbers · Spelling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">greetings (U1)</span><span class="vr">am/is/are (U1)</span><span class="vr">Nice to meet you (U1)</span><span class="vr">What's your name? (U1)</span><span class="vr">numbers 1–100</span><span class="vr">age</span><span class="vr">address</span><span class="vr">email</span><span class="vr">How do you spell…?</span><span class="vr">a/an</span><span class="vr">Wh- questions</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Gap</div><div class="ad">Student A has a form with some information missing. Student B has the missing info. They ask Wh- questions using to be to complete their forms. Forces real communication.</div><div class=ap>What's her name? — Her name is Sara. How old is she? — She's 34. Where is she from? — She's from Russia. What's her phone number? — It's 07700 900 461.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Speed Networking</div><div class="ad">90 seconds per partner. Students exchange: name, age, country, job/study, email. Must spell email aloud. Timer creates real pressure.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Class Directory</div><div class="ad">Students compile a class directory by interviewing everyone. Final product: a real list with names, ages, countries, emails — all spoken, all using Units 1+2 grammar.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Greatest Quotes</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: A number that changed your life · Full Units 1–2 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">💬 THE GREATEST QUOTES — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">A number that changed your life — an age, a year, a phone number you'll never forget.</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Say three numbers that are important to you." Partner guesses what they mean using to be: "Is it your age? Is it your phone number?"</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Tell the story of your number. "I am 32 now but I was 18 when I moved to France. Eighteen is an important number for me." Simple sentences, all to be, all numbers.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher notes Wh- question errors (wrong word order, missing to be). Corrects live. Boards 3 correct student sentences.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge (90 sec):</strong> "Talk about yourself — your name, age, where you are from, your most important number. Spell something. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">📌 Units 1+2 fully active: to be (all forms) · Wh- questions · numbers 1–100 · a/an · alphabet. Teacher notes remaining passive vocabulary.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 2 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1 + 2</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">▼</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write numbers 1–100: 10 numbers given as digits, write in words</div><div class=ei>Write ordinals: 1st–10th in full words</div><div class=ei>Spell 3 names read aloud by the teacher</div><div class=ei>Fill: "I ___ 29 years old. I live ___ Paris. My email ___ sara@mail.com."</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write Wh- questions for given answers: "I'm 31." / "She's from Italy." / "It's 020 7946 0000."</div><div class=ei>Choose a or an: ___ engineer / ___ old city / ___ student / ___ address / ___ phone</div><div class=ei>Make plurals: class / person / address / teacher / child</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences mixing Units 1+2 errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Introduce yourself fully: name (spell it), age, country, job — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 Wh- questions using to be</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 questions about personal information using full sentences</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a short personal profile (6–8 sentences). Must include: Wh- question answered in writing (×2) · a/an (×2) · numbers (×3) · a plural noun.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(0)">← Unit 1</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(2)">Unit 3 →</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-2"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 3 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Family</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn all family relationships and describe people. Have got and possessives complete the grammar picture started in Unit 1.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:14%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: am/is/are · Wh- questions · a/an · numbers 1-100 · greetings</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Family</div><div class="lesson-sub">am/is/are · Wh- questions · a/an · numbers 1-100 · greetings…</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · Wh- questions · a/an · numbers 1-100 · greetings</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">mother/mum/father/dad</div><div class="vd">parents</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">brother/sister</div><div class="vd">siblings</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">son/daughter</div><div class="vd">children</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">grandmother/grandfather</div><div class="vd">grandparents</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">husband/wife/partner</div><div class="vd">spouse/partner</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">aunt/uncle/cousin</div><div class="vd">extended family</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">nephew/niece</div><div class="vd">siblings children</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">married/single/divorced</div><div class="vd">relationship status</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">only child/twins</div><div class="vd">number of children</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">young/old/middle-aged</div><div class="vd">age descriptions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Have Got, Possessive Adjectives: my/your/his/her/our/their, Possessive 's</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Have Got</div><div class=ge>Use alongside to be to show possession and family.</div><div class="ex">I've got a sister. / She's got two brothers.</div><div class="ex">Have you got cousins? — Yes, I have. / No, I haven't.</div><div class="ex">He hasn't got a wife — he is single.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Possessive Adjectives: my/your/his/her/our/their</div><div class=ge>Direct extension of Unit 1 pronouns.</div><div class="ex">I am → my name. She is → her mother. They are → their family.</div><div class="ex">His grandmother is 80. / Her cousin is from Italy.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Possessive 's</div><div class=ge>Add 's to a name to show belonging — different from the contraction 's = is.</div><div class="ex">Ana's brother is 30. (possession)</div><div class="ex">My father's sister is my aunt.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Family</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · Wh- questions · a/an · numbers 1-100 · greetings + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">Let's Celebrate</div><div class="st">A family celebration — who is there, ages, where from, what you do together.</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Name one family member. How old? Where from?" — to be + age + country instantly.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Describe a family gathering. Who comes? "My grandmother's got 8 grandchildren. We are all from different countries!"</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Teacher checks his/her/their confusion — most common possessive error.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Describe your family — ages, countries, how many people. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-3: to be + have got + possessives + numbers + countries all active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 3 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–3</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(1)">Back: Unit 2</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(3)">Unit 4</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-3"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 4 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Home &amp; Rooms</div><div class="unit-desc">Students describe where they live, the rooms in their home and basic furniture. There is/there are is introduced as a major new grammar point that recycles all prior vocabulary.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:18%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: am/is/are · have got · possessives · numbers · family words · countries</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Home & Rooms</div><div class="lesson-sub">am/is/are · have got · possessives · numbers · family words …</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · possessives · numbers · family words · countries</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">house/flat/apartment/studio</div><div class="vd">home types</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">kitchen/bedroom/bathroom/living room/dining room</div><div class="vd">rooms</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">garden/balcony/hall/garage</div><div class="vd">outdoor and extra spaces</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">sofa/bed/table/chair/wardrobe</div><div class="vd">furniture</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">window/door/wall/floor/ceiling</div><div class="vd">parts of a room</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">big/small/old/new/modern/beautiful/cosy</div><div class="vd">home adjectives — expands U1 adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">upstairs/downstairs/on the first floor</div><div class="vd">position in a building</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I live in a… / I rent / I own</div><div class="vd">housing situation</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">There is / There are, Adjective Position — before the noun always</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">There is / There are</div><div class=ge>Use to introduce what exists in a space. Contrast carefully with it is/they are (U1).</div><div class="ex">There is a sofa in my living room. / It is big and comfortable. (to be = description)</div><div class="ex">There are two bedrooms in my flat.</div><div class="ex">Is there a garden? — Yes, there is. / No, there isn't.</div><div class="ex">Are there any windows? — Yes, there are three.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Adjective Position — before the noun always</div><div class=ge>Extends Unit 1 knowledge of adjectives to all home vocabulary.</div><div class="ex">a big modern kitchen / a small cosy bedroom / an old beautiful house</div><div class="ex">There is a comfortable blue sofa. (TWO adjectives — order: opinion + colour)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Home & Rooms</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · possessives · numbers · family words · countries + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">My Life With & Without</div><div class="st">Life with and without your own space — a room, a flat, a home.</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Describe your home in 3 sentences. Use there is/are." — new grammar activated immediately.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Have you always lived in the same home? What is your dream home like? "My dream home has got 5 bedrooms. There is a big garden and a modern kitchen."</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Teacher collects there is vs it is errors. Quick discrimination drill.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Describe your home and your dream home. Use there is/are + adjectives. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-4: to be + have got + there is/are + adjectives + numbers + family all active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 4 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–4</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(2)">Back: Unit 3</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(4)">Unit 5</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-4"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 5 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Daily Routine</div><div class="unit-desc">Present simple is the most important new grammar point of A1 Part 1. Numbers now serve as clock times. Family and home vocabulary from earlier units are embedded in every routine discussion.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:23%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: am/is/are · have got · there is/are · numbers as times · family · rooms · adjectives</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Daily Routine</div><div class="lesson-sub">am/is/are · have got · there is/are · numbers as times · fam…</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · there is/are · numbers as times · family · rooms · adjectives</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">wake up/get up</div><div class="vd">start of day</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">have breakfast/lunch/dinner</div><div class="vd">meals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">go to work/school/university</div><div class="vd">daily movement</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">start/finish work</div><div class="vd">begin and end</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">go home/come home</div><div class="vd">return</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">watch TV/read/cook/clean</div><div class="vd">home activities</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">go to bed/fall asleep</div><div class="vd">end of day</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">in the morning/afternoon/evening/at night</div><div class="vd">parts of day</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Monday/Tuesday/Wednesday/Thursday/Friday/Saturday/Sunday</div><div class="vd">days of the week</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">o'clock/half past/quarter past/quarter to</div><div class="vd">clock expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">always/usually/often/sometimes/rarely/never</div><div class="vd">frequency adverbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">early/late/on time</div><div class="vd">manner of timing</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Present Simple — Positive, Do/Does — Questions and Negatives, Frequency Adverb Position</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Present Simple — Positive</div><div class=ge>For habits and routines. Third person he/she/it adds -s. Never confuse with to be.</div><div class="ex">I wake up at 7. / She wakes up at 8. (not: she wake up)</div><div class="ex">He goes to work by bus. / We have breakfast at 7:30.</div><div class="ex">She IS a teacher. (to be) / She TEACHES at school. (present simple) — KEY CONTRAST</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Do/Does — Questions and Negatives</div><div class=ge>Never use is/are for present simple questions — the most common A1 error. Drill constantly.</div><div class="ex">Do you wake up early? — Yes, I do. / No, I don't.</div><div class="ex">Does she eat breakfast? — Yes, she does. / No, she doesn't.</div><div class="ex">I don't go to work on Sundays. / He doesn't watch TV in the morning.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Frequency Adverb Position</div><div class=ge>Before the main verb — BUT after to be.</div><div class="ex">I always wake up at 7. (before main verb)</div><div class="ex">She is always late. (after to be — recycled from U1)</div><div class="ex">My father sometimes reads in the living room. (room from U4)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Daily Routine</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · there is/are · numbers as times · family · rooms · adjectives + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">Mind Matters</div><div class="st">Morning routines and energy — what does your mind need to start the day?</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Describe your morning in 30 seconds using only words we know." Timer adds pressure.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you always wake up at the same time? Does your family have breakfast together? How is your energy in the morning?</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Collect do/does confusion with is/are. Quick discrimination drill.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Talk about a typical Monday for you and one family member. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-5: present simple + to be + have got + there is/are + numbers + family + rooms — all active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 5 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–5</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(3)">Back: Unit 4</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(5)">Unit 6</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-5"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 6 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Food &amp; Drink</div><div class="unit-desc">Students talk about food preferences, order in a cafe and describe meals. Countable vs uncountable nouns and some/any are the key new grammar points.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:27%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: am/is/are · have got · present simple · do/does · frequency adverbs · numbers · family · rooms · daily activities</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Food & Drink</div><div class="lesson-sub">am/is/are · have got · present simple · do/does · frequency …</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · present simple · do/does · frequency adverbs · numbers · family · rooms · daily activities</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bread/rice/pasta/meat/fish</div><div class="vd">staple foods</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">vegetables/fruit/salad/soup</div><div class="vd">healthy foods</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">coffee/tea/water/juice/milk/wine/beer</div><div class="vd">drinks</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">breakfast/lunch/dinner/snack</div><div class="vd">meals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">sweet/salty/spicy/sour/bitter/delicious/horrible</div><div class="vd">taste adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">hot/cold/warm/fresh</div><div class="vd">temperature and freshness</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">a cup of/a glass of/a bottle of/a slice of/a piece of</div><div class="vd">containers and portions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">hungry/thirsty/full/starving</div><div class="vd">feelings about food</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">like/love/hate/don't like/prefer</div><div class="vd">preference verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">twenty to one hundred</div><div class="vd">numbers 21-100 — prices</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Countable vs Uncountable Nouns, Some / Any / How much / How many</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Countable vs Uncountable Nouns</div><div class=ge>Countable = can count and have plurals. Uncountable = no plural, never use a/an.</div><div class="ex">Countable: an apple / two apples / some apples / how many apples?</div><div class="ex">Uncountable: milk / some milk / any water / how much milk? (never: a milk)</div><div class="ex">Bread is uncountable but: a slice of bread / a loaf of bread (portion words make it countable)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Some / Any / How much / How many</div><div class=ge>Some in positives. Any in negatives and questions. How many with countable. How much with uncountable.</div><div class="ex">I have some bread. / There is some milk. (positive)</div><div class="ex">I don't have any eggs. / Is there any coffee? (negative/question — recycles don't/doesn't U5)</div><div class="ex">How many apples? / How much milk? — How much is it? (price — recycles numbers)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Food & Drink</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · present simple · do/does · frequency adverbs · numbers · family · rooms · daily activities + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">Let's Celebrate</div><div class="st">A dish from your culture — what do you eat on a special day?</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Name your favourite food. Is it sweet, salty or spicy? Does your family love it too?"</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Describe a traditional dish. What is in it? Is there any meat? How much does it cost to make? When do you eat it?</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Collect there is/there are vs it is errors + countable/uncountable mistakes.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Describe your favourite meal — what it is, who makes it, what's in it. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-6: there is/are + some/any + present simple + to be + have got + numbers 1-100 all active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 6 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–6</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(4)">Back: Unit 5</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(6)">Unit 7</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-6"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 7 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Places in Town</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to name and describe places in a city. There is/there are is now used with city vocabulary. Can/can't for possibility is introduced alongside all prior grammar.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:32%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · some/any · numbers · food vocabulary</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Places in Town</div><div class="lesson-sub">am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · some/…</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · some/any · numbers · food vocabulary</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">cafe/restaurant/bar/pub</div><div class="vd">eating and drinking places — expands food vocab</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">shop/supermarket/market/bakery/pharmacy</div><div class="vd">shopping places</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">school/university/hospital/clinic</div><div class="vd">education and health</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">park/square/library/museum/cinema/theatre</div><div class="vd">leisure places</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bank/post office/police station/town hall</div><div class="vd">services</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">near/far/next to/opposite/between/behind/in front of</div><div class="vd">prepositions of place</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">on the corner of/at the end of/in the centre</div><div class="vd">location expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">open/closed/busy/quiet/crowded/empty</div><div class="vd">place adjectives</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Can/Can't — ability and possibility, Prepositions of Place — in/on/at/next to/opposite</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Can/Can't — ability and possibility</div><div class=ge>Can never changes form — no -s for he/she. This directly contrasts with present simple where he/she adds -s.</div><div class="ex">I can walk to school. / She can drive. (NOT: she cans)</div><div class="ex">Can you speak French? — Yes, I can. / No, I can't.</div><div class="ex">You can park here. / You can't smoke inside. (rules/possibility)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Prepositions of Place — in/on/at/next to/opposite</div><div class=ge>In = inside a space. On = surface or street. At = specific point.</div><div class="ex">I live in Paris. (city) / My flat is on Baker Street. (street name)</div><div class="ex">The cafe is at number 12. / I am at the bank now.</div><div class="ex">The park is next to the school, opposite the supermarket.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Places in Town</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · some/any · numbers · food vocabulary + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">My Life With & Without</div><div class="st">Life with and without your favourite place in the city.</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Name your favourite place in your city. What is it? Where is it exactly?" — prepositions activated immediately.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Why is this place important to you? Can you walk there? Is it near your home? Is it always busy?</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Collect in/on/at errors. Contrast can with present simple (habits vs possibility).</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Describe your city and your favourite places. Use can + prepositions. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-7: can/can't + prepositions + there is/are + present simple + to be + all vocabulary domains active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 7 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–7</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(5)">Back: Unit 6</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(7)">Unit 8</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-7"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 8 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Transport &amp; Directions</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to navigate a city, take transport and give directions. All city vocabulary from Unit 7 is now combined with transport and directional language.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:36%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: can/can't · prepositions · there is/are · present simple · numbers (times/prices) · places in town</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Transport & Directions</div><div class="lesson-sub">can/can't · prepositions · there is/are · present simple · n…</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">can/can't · prepositions · there is/are · present simple · numbers (times/prices) · places in town</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bus/train/metro/tram/taxi/bicycle/car/ferry</div><div class="vd">transport types</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bus stop/train station/airport/port</div><div class="vd">transport hubs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">ticket/single/return/platform/departure/arrival</div><div class="vd">travel words</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">turn left/turn right/go straight on/take the first left</div><div class="vd">directions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How do you get to…?/Excuse me where is…?</div><div class="vd">asking for help</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">on foot/by bus/by car/by metro</div><div class="vd">transport manner</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How long does it take?/It takes 10 minutes</div><div class="vd">journey duration — recycles numbers</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">too far/not far/about 5 minutes</div><div class="vd">distance expressions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">How to Get There — Questions with How, Imperatives for Directions</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">How to Get There — Questions with How</div><div class=ge>Extends Wh- questions from Unit 2 to transport situations.</div><div class="ex">How do you get to work? — I take the metro.</div><div class="ex">How long does it take? — It takes about 20 minutes.</div><div class="ex">How much is a ticket? — It's two euros fifty. (numbers recycled)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Imperatives for Directions</div><div class=ge>Use the base verb with no subject for instructions and directions.</div><div class="ex">Turn left at the park. / Go straight on for 200 metres.</div><div class="ex">Take the number 7 bus. / Get off at the station.</div><div class="ex">Don't turn right — go straight on! (negative imperative)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Transport & Directions</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">can/can't · prepositions · there is/are · present simple · numbers (times/prices) · places in town + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">My Life With & Without</div><div class="st">Life with and without a car — how transport shapes your daily routine.</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "How did you get here today?" — can + transport + prepositions activated immediately in a real context.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Have you got a car? Can you drive? Where do you usually go by metro/bus? How long does it take to get to work?</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Collect imperative errors + how long/how far confusion.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Describe your week — where you go, how you get there, how long it takes. Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-8: imperatives + how questions + can + prepositions + present simple + all prior vocabulary active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 8 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–8</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(6)">Back: Unit 7</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(8)">Unit 9</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-8"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 9 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Shopping &amp; Prices</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to shop, ask prices and make transactions. Numbers 1-100 are now used constantly for prices. All food, places and transport vocabulary is recycled in shopping contexts.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:41%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: can/can't · present simple · have got · there is/are · numbers 1-100 · places in town · food vocabulary</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Shopping & Prices</div><div class="lesson-sub">can/can't · present simple · have got · there is/are · numbe…</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">can/can't · present simple · have got · there is/are · numbers 1-100 · places in town · food vocabulary</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">shop/store/market/mall</div><div class="vd">shopping places</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How much is it?/How much does it cost?/It costs…</div><div class="vd">price questions — recycles numbers</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">cheap/expensive/good value/a bargain</div><div class="vd">price adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">pay/buy/sell/spend/save/change/receipt</div><div class="vd">shopping verbs and nouns</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">cash/card/coin/note/wallet</div><div class="vd">payment vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I'd like…/I'll take it./Can I have…?/Just looking, thanks.</div><div class="vd">shopping phrases</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">size: small/medium/large/extra large</div><div class="vd">sizes</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">too big/too small/too expensive/just right</div><div class="vd">shopping reactions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Would Like — polite desire, This/That/These/Those — demonstratives</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Would Like — polite desire</div><div class=ge>Contrast with like (habit, Unit 6) and want (direct desire).</div><div class="ex">I like coffee. (habit) / I want a coffee. (direct) / I'd like a coffee, please. (polite)</div><div class="ex">Would you like to pay by card? — Yes, please. / No, I'd prefer cash.</div><div class="ex">She'd like a medium, please. / We'd like two tickets.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">This/That/These/Those — demonstratives</div><div class=ge>Near vs far. Singular vs plural — links to countable/uncountable (U6).</div><div class="ex">This shirt is beautiful. (near, singular) / These shoes are expensive. (near, plural)</div><div class="ex">That red coat is thirty euros. (far, singular) / Those trousers are too small. (far, plural)</div><div class="ex">Can I have this one? / I'd like those, please.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Shopping & Prices</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">can/can't · present simple · have got · there is/are · numbers 1-100 · places in town · food vocabulary + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">Debatable & Relatable</div><div class="st">Online shopping is destroying real shops — do you agree?</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Do you like shopping? What do you usually buy? Where do you go?" — present simple + places + food instantly.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: Build a position. "I can buy everything online. There are big shops near my house but they are expensive. I always pay by card."</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Audit of would like vs like vs want confusion. Quick drill.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: "Describe your shopping habits. Where, when, how much do you spend? Don't stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1-9: would like + this/that/these/those + can + present simple + numbers + all vocabulary active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 9 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–9</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(7)">Back: Unit 8</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(9)">Unit 10</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-9"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 10 of 36</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Colours &amp; Clothes</div><div class="unit-desc">The final Part 1 unit. Object pronouns complete the full pronoun system started in Unit 1. Every vocabulary domain and all grammar points from Part 1 are spiralled into this unit and the Part 1 final exam.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:45%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">Spiral recycling: ALL Part 1 grammar: am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · can · would like · this/that · possessives · numbers</div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Colours & Clothes</div><div class="lesson-sub">ALL Part 1 grammar: am/is/are · have got · present simple · …</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Previous Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">ALL Part 1 grammar: am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · can · would like · this/that · possessives · numbers</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">red/blue/green/yellow/black/white/pink/orange/purple/grey/brown/beige</div><div class="vd">colours</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">T-shirt/shirt/blouse/dress/skirt/trousers/jeans/shorts</div><div class="vd">clothing tops and bottoms</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">shoes/boots/trainers/sandals/socks</div><div class="vd">footwear</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">jacket/coat/scarf/hat/gloves/belt/bag</div><div class="vd">outerwear and accessories</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">wear/put on/take off/try on/fit/suit</div><div class="vd">clothing verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What are you wearing?/I'm wearing…</div><div class="vd">describing current clothes</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I'm looking for…/Do you have it in…?</div><div class="vd">shopping for clothes — recycles Unit 9</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">pattern: striped/checked/plain/floral</div><div class="vd">describing patterns</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary in Context</div><div class="ad">Students use new words immediately in sentences with grammar from previous units — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Sentences</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences using new vocabulary + one grammar point from each previous unit.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Object Pronouns — me/you/him/her/it/us/them, Present Continuous — I am wearing (preview)</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Object Pronouns — me/you/him/her/it/us/them</div><div class=ge>Completes the full pronoun system from Unit 1. Replaces object nouns to avoid repetition.</div><div class="ex">I like this jacket. → I like it. / She wants those shoes. → She wants them.</div><div class="ex">Can you help me? / She wants to see him. / I can give them the receipt.</div><div class="ex">My mother loves this dress. → She loves it. (it = the dress)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Present Continuous — I am wearing (preview)</div><div class=ge>Brief introduction as a description tool for clothes being worn now — fully taught in A2 Part 1.</div><div class="ex">I am wearing a blue shirt today. / She is wearing a beautiful red dress.</div><div class="ex">What are you wearing? — I'm wearing jeans and a grey jacket.</div><div class="ex">He isn't wearing a coat — he is cold! (to be recycled naturally)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Discrimination Drill</div><div class="ad">Students identify which grammar rule applies in 10 mixed sentences — new grammar vs all prior grammar points.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">Fix 5 sentences with errors from the new grammar point. Then fix 3 sentences with errors from previous units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Colours & Clothes</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral of all units so far</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">ALL Part 1 grammar: am/is/are · have got · present simple · there is/are · can · would like · this/that · possessives · numbers + ALL new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Integrated Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students use ALL grammar points from all units so far in a structured conversation. No grammar point may be left unused.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Information Hunt</div><div class="ad">Mingle activity requiring students to form questions and answers using new vocabulary + all prior grammar.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 2-min story incorporating all vocabulary domains covered so far.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">Spoken Club · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">Let's Celebrate</div><div class="st">Getting dressed for a celebration — what do you wear and why?</div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>1</div><span>Warm-up: "Describe what you are wearing today using colours + clothes." — Present continuous preview activated immediately.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>2</div><span>Main conversation: What do you wear for special occasions? Does your family dress up? Is there a traditional outfit from your country?</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>3</div><span>Language in action: Full Part 1 grammar audit — teacher tracks which students use all 7 grammar points spontaneously.</span></div><div class=sstep><div class=sn>4</div><span>Fluency challenge 3 min: "Tell me about your life — your family, your home, your routine, what you eat, where you go, what you wear. Use everything. Don't stop." — Complete Part 1 oral rehearsal.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; FULL Part 1 spiral: all 7 grammar points + all 10 vocabulary domains active. Teacher produces personalised gap notes before the Part 1 exam.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 10 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–10</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify and write 8 words from this unit from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Match vocabulary to categories covered in this unit</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using new vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences using new words + grammar from any previous unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Discrimination task: choose the correct grammar form from all units so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences — 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task using the unit topic + all prior vocabulary domains</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions covering vocabulary and grammar from this unit</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class=ed>Write a paragraph of 8-10 sentences on this unit's topic. Must include the new grammar point (x2) + grammar from at least 3 previous units + vocabulary from at least 3 different topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(8)">Back: Unit 9</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(10)">Unit 11 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-10"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 11 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 1</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">&#127807; Part 1 — Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Countries &amp; Nationalities</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn all key nationalities, languages and continents. The crucial distinction between <em>I am Italian</em> (nationality, to be) and <em>I speak Italian</em> (language, present simple) is formally taught and drilled. Capital letters for nationalities are established.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:37%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> am/is/are (U1) · Wh- questions (U2) · a/an (U2) · present simple (U5) · all prior vocabulary</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Countries &amp; Nationalities</div><div class="lesson-sub">Country names · Nationality adjectives · Languages · Continents</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–10</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">I am from… (U1)</span><span class="vr">am/is/are (U1)</span><span class="vr">Where are you from? (U2)</span><span class="vr">a/an (U2) — a/an Italian / a/an English speaker</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">England → English / Britain → British</div><div class="vd">nationality from country</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">France → French</div><div class="vd">nationality from country</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Italy → Italian</div><div class="vd">nationality from country</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Russia → Russian</div><div class="vd">nationality from country</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Greece → Greek</div><div class="vd">nationality from country</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Spain → Spanish / Germany → German</div><div class="vd">more nationalities</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Japan → Japanese / China → Chinese / Brazil → Brazilian</div><div class="vd">world nationalities</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">America → American / Canada → Canadian / Australia → Australian</div><div class="vd">English-speaking countries</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Europe / Asia / Africa / North America / South America / Oceania</div><div class="vd">continents</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I speak English / French / Italian / Russian / Greek</div><div class="vd">languages</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What language do you speak? / What is your nationality?</div><div class="vd">nationality questions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I am Italian. / She is French. / They are Russian.</div><div class="vd">nationality adjectives with to be</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Country–Nationality–Language Drill</div><div class="ad">Three columns on the board: country / nationality / language. Students fill in the missing cells. Rapid-fire: teacher says country, students say nationality immediately.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Who am I?</div><div class="ad">Teacher describes a famous person using nationality + language + one fact. Students guess. All sentences use to be (U1).</div><div class=ap>She is French. She speaks French and English. She is a very famous singer. → Is she Celine Dion? — No, she is not Canadian — she is French!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Class Map</div><div class="ad">Students mark their countries on a blank world map, write their nationality and language. Present to the class using: I am [nationality]. I am from [country]. I speak [language].</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Nationality Adjectives · Languages · To Be Review</div><div class="lesson-sub">Adjective agrees with person, not noun · I speak vs I am · Capital letters for nationalities</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–10</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are (U1)</span><span class="vr">subject pronouns (U1)</span><span class="vr">a/an (U2)</span><span class="vr">Wh- questions (U2)</span><span class="vr">present simple (U5)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Nationality as Adjective with To Be</div><div class="ge">['I am Italian. / She is French. / They are Russian. (not: They are Russians)', 'He is a French man. / She is an Italian woman. (a/an from U2 recycled)', 'Are you American? — No, I am not. I am Canadian.', 'What nationality are you? — I am Greek.']</div><div class="ex">N</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">j</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">f</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">—</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">.</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">T</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">w</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Speak vs Be — two different verbs</div><div class="ge">['I am Italian. I speak Italian and English. (to be + present simple)', 'She is French but she speaks English very well.', 'Do you speak Russian? — Yes, I do. (present simple question, U5)', 'Is she Russian? — Yes, she is. (to be question, U1)']</div><div class="ex">I</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">I</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">(</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex">)</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">N</div><div class="ex">O</div><div class="ex">T</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">I</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">k</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">I</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">(</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">)</div><div class="ex">.</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">S</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">f</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex">.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Capital Letters — always for nationalities and languages</div><div class="ge">['italian ✗ → Italian ✓ / french ✗ → French ✓', 'I speak english ✗ → I speak English ✓', 'She is a russian teacher ✗ → She is a Russian teacher ✓']</div><div class="ex">I</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">E</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">,</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">j</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">A</div><div class="ex">L</div><div class="ex">W</div><div class="ex">A</div><div class="ex">Y</div><div class="ex">S</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Am vs Speak Discrimination</div><div class="ad">12 sentences — students decide: does this sentence need to be or present simple (speak)?</div><div class=ap>"She ___ Italian." → Is she Italian? (to be) or Does she speak Italian? (present simple) — context decides!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Correction</div><div class="ad">8 sentences with nationality/capital letter errors. Students correct and explain the rule.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Nationalities &amp; Languages in Conversation</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: Units 1–11 · to be · present simple · Wh- questions · a/an</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–11</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">greetings (U1)</span><span class="vr">am/is/are (U1)</span><span class="vr">numbers/ages (U2)</span><span class="vr">family words (U3)</span><span class="vr">rooms (U4)</span><span class="vr">present simple (U5)</span><span class="vr">food (U6)</span><span class="vr">places (U7)</span><span class="vr">transport (U8)</span><span class="vr">shopping (U9)</span><span class="vr">colours (U10)</span><span class="vr">nationalities/languages</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Nationality Mingle</div><div class="ad">Students walk around. Each person asks: "What nationality are you? Do you speak any other languages?" Must use am for nationality and speak (present simple) for languages. Corrects the most common confusion.</div><div class=ap>Are you Italian? — Yes, I am. / What languages do you speak? — I speak Italian and a little English. / Do you speak French? — No, I do not. Are you French? — No, I am Greek!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Flag Quiz</div><div class="ad">Teacher shows a flag. Students race to say: "[Country name]. The nationality is [nationality]. They speak [language]." Brings in a/an: "It is an Italian flag."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My International Family</div><div class="ad">Students describe their family tree (U3) now adding nationalities. Forces integration of Units 1–11.</div><div class=ap>My grandmother is Greek. She speaks Greek and a little French. My father is Italian but he speaks English very well. His mother is British — she is my British grandmother!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Let's Celebrate</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: A national celebration from your country · Units 1–11 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#127881; LET'S CELEBRATE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">A national celebration from your country — what is it, when is it, and what do people do?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Say your nationality and one thing that makes your country special." — nationality vocabulary + to be + present simple activated immediately.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Describe a national holiday or celebration. What do people eat? What do they wear? Is it similar to celebrations in other countries? "I am Greek. We celebrate Easter very differently from Italian people. We eat lamb and we go to church at midnight."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher checks am (nationality) vs speak (language) confusion — the most important distinction of this unit. Also checks capital letters in written work.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Tell me about your nationality and country — the language, the food, the celebrations, the people. Use everything you know. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1–11 fully active: to be + nationalities + languages + present simple + food + celebrations. Teacher notes capital letter errors for written correction.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 11 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–11</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write the nationality for 10 countries: France → ___ / Italy → ___ etc.</div><div class=ei>Write the language spoken in 8 countries</div><div class=ei>Place 8 countries on the correct continent</div><div class=ei>Fill: "She ___ French. She ___ French and English." (am/is/speaks)</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Choose am/is/are OR speak/speaks for 10 sentences</div><div class=ei>Correct 4 nationality sentences: capital letter errors + wrong form</div><div class=ei>Write nationality questions and answers for 4 given situations</div><div class=ei>Discrimination: 6 sentences — is she Italian? (nationality) vs does she speak Italian? (language)</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Introduce yourself: name, age, nationality, language(s), country — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Describe 3 family members including their nationality and language</div><div class=ei>Compare your country's celebrations to another country — 2 min</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences about yourself and your country. Must include: nationality adjective with to be (×3) · speak/speaks (×2) · a/an + nationality (×2) · present simple (×2) · one family member with their nationality.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(9)">&#8592; Unit 10</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(11)">Unit 12 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-11"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 12 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 1</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">&#127807; Part 1 — Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Physical Appearance</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to describe what people look like — height, build, hair, eyes and general features. The grammar distinction between <em>have got</em> (for features) and <em>look</em> (for observation) and <em>look like</em> (for resemblance) is formally established.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:40%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> have got (U3) · am/is/are (U1) · adjectives (U4) · nationalities (U11) · family (U3)</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Physical Appearance</div><div class="lesson-sub">Height · Build · Hair · Eyes · Age descriptions · General appearance</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–11</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are (U1)</span><span class="vr">have got (U3)</span><span class="vr">adjectives (U4)</span><span class="vr">nationalities (U11)</span><span class="vr">family words (U3) — describing relatives</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">tall / medium height / short</div><div class="vd">height</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">slim / thin / average build / heavy / muscular</div><div class="vd">build</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">long / short / shoulder-length</div><div class="vd">hair length</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">straight / curly / wavy</div><div class="vd">hair type</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">dark / light / fair / blond / brown / black / red / grey / white</div><div class="vd">hair colour</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bald / shaved head</div><div class="vd">no hair</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">blue / green / brown / grey / dark / light</div><div class="vd">eye colour</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">young / middle-aged / elderly</div><div class="vd">age appearance</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">beautiful / handsome / attractive / pretty / cute</div><div class="vd">general appearance — careful: use respectfully</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">beard / moustache / glasses / freckles / tattoo</div><div class="vd">distinguishing features</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">He/She looks like… / He/She looks + adjective</div><div class="vd">appearance expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">They look similar. / They look different.</div><div class="vd">comparison of appearance</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Describe and Draw</div><div class="ad">Student A describes a person (real or imaginary) using appearance vocabulary. Student B draws them. Compare results. Forces precise vocabulary use.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Who in the Class?</div><div class="ad">Teacher gives a description using appearance words. Students guess who it is. No names — only descriptions.</div><div class=ap>She has got long curly brown hair. She is quite tall. She has got brown eyes. → Is it Maria? — Yes, it is!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Celebrity Guess</div><div class="ad">Students describe a famous person's appearance. Class guesses. Integrates nationalities (U11) naturally: "He is tall. He has got short dark hair. He is American."</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Have Got for Appearance · Look + Adjective · Look Like</div><div class="lesson-sub">She has got blue eyes · She looks tired · She looks like her mother</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="l