s="ex">i</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Look Like — resemblance</div><div class="ge">['She looks like her mother. / He looks like a teacher.', 'They look like twins! / It looks like a castle.', 'She looks beautiful. (adjective) vs She looks like a model. (noun) — KEY contrast']</div><div class="ex">L</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">k</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">k</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">f</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">w</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">b</div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">(</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">)</div><div class="ex">,</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">j</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Have Got or Look?</div><div class="ad">10 sentences — students choose: "She ___ blue eyes." (has got) vs "She ___ happy." (looks). Forces the distinction between possession and observation.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Adjective or Noun after Look Like?</div><div class="ad">Students complete sentences choosing correctly: "She looks ___ (tired/a doctor/beautiful/like a student)."</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Describe People Around You</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: Units 1–12 · have got · look + adjective · look like · nationalities</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–12</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">am/is/are</span><span class="vr">have got</span><span class="vr">family words</span><span class="vr">adjectives</span><span class="vr">nationalities (U11)</span><span class="vr">height/build/hair/eyes</span><span class="vr">look + adjective</span><span class="vr">look like</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Guess Who?</div><div class="ad">Classic game. Student A thinks of someone in the class (or a celebrity). Class asks yes/no questions using have got and look.</div><div class=ap>Has she got long hair? — Yes, she has. / Does she look young? — Yes, she does. / Is she tall? — No, she is not. → Is it Ana? — Yes!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Family Resemblance</div><div class="ad">Students describe physical similarities between family members (U3) using look like and have got.</div><div class=ap>My mother and my sister look like each other. They have both got curly brown hair and green eyes. My brother looks like my father — they are both tall and slim. I look like my grandmother — she has got the same freckles!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Perfect Flatmate</div><div class="ad">Students describe the ideal flatmate's appearance and personality using all vocabulary. Integrates home (U4), food (U6), daily routine (U5) naturally.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With &amp; Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: A person who changed your life — what do they look like? · Units 1–12 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Describe someone who changed your life — who are they, what do they look like, what did they give you?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Describe one person in this room using only appearance words — no name." Appearance vocabulary activated in 60 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Who is the most important person in your life? Describe them physically and as a person. "My grandmother is short and slim. She has got white hair and brown eyes. She looks kind. She looks like a person who has lived a wonderful life."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher checks have got (appearance) vs look (observation) vs look like (resemblance). All three must be distinct in student production.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Describe someone important to you — their appearance, their nationality, where they live, what they do. Use everything you know. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1–12: have got + look + look like + nationalities + family + adjectives all active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 12 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–12</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Label physical features on a picture: 8 items</div><div class=ei>Match appearance adjectives to descriptions</div><div class=ei>Write hair descriptions: length + type + colour for 4 pictures</div><div class=ei>Choose: tall/short/slim/heavy/muscular for 4 body descriptions</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete with has got OR looks: "She ___ blue eyes. / She ___ tired."</div><div class=ei>Complete with look OR look like: "He ___ his father. / She ___ beautiful."</div><div class=ei>Write 3 appearance questions using have got</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences mixing have got / look / look like errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your own appearance in full — 60 seconds</div><div class=ei>Play Guess Who? with the examiner — ask 5 yes/no questions using have got and look</div><div class=ei>Describe a family member's appearance and compare them to another family member — 2 min</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph describing a real or imaginary person (8–10 sentences). Must include: have got (×4 — appearance features) · look + adjective (×2) · look like (×1) · nationality (×1) · adjective before noun (×2).</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(10)">&#8592; Unit 11</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(12)">Unit 13 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-12"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 13 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 1</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">&#127807; Part 1 — Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Classroom Language</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn all essential classroom language — instructions, requests, objects and study vocabulary. This unit is taught through the language itself, making it immediately practical. Imperatives are formally completed and <em>can</em> for requests is distinguished from <em>can</em> for ability.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:43%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> imperatives (U8) · can/can't (U7) · Wh- questions (U2) · am/is/are (U1) · present simple (U5)</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Classroom Language &amp; Learning</div><div class="lesson-sub">Classroom instructions · Objects · Asking for help · Study verbs · Learning phrases</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–12</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">Excuse me / Sorry (U1)</span><span class="vr">Can you repeat that? (U1)</span><span class="vr">I do not understand (U1)</span><span class="vr">imperatives (U8)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Open / Close your book. / Turn to page…</div><div class="vd">teacher instructions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Listen / Repeat / Read / Write / Spell / Translate</div><div class="vd">learning verbs — imperatives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Look at the board. / Work in pairs. / Work in groups.</div><div class="vd">classroom instructions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">book / notebook / pen / pencil / rubber / ruler / dictionary / board</div><div class="vd">classroom objects</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I do not understand. / Can you explain that again? / More slowly, please.</div><div class="vd">asking for clarification</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How do you say ___ in English? / What does ___ mean?</div><div class="vd">translation and meaning questions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How do you spell ___? / Can you write it on the board?</div><div class="vd">spelling and writing requests</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Is this correct? / Am I right? / Can you check this?</div><div class="vd">asking for feedback</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">study / practise / revise / remember / forget / improve</div><div class="vd">learning process verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">homework / exercise / test / exam / lesson / class / course</div><div class="vd">study vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">difficult / easy / interesting / boring / useful / important</div><div class="vd">learning adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I know. / I do not know. / I think… / I am not sure.</div><div class="vd">expressing certainty</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Teacher Says</div><div class="ad">Simon Says format using only classroom instructions. Students must follow only when teacher says the full instruction correctly. All imperatives (U8) recycled.</div><div class=ap>Listen! / Repeat! / Open your book! / Look at the board! / Write your name!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Classroom Object Hunt</div><div class="ad">Students label everything in the classroom in English. Then one student describes an object using: colour (U10) + size (U4) + what it is for. Class guesses.</div><div class=ap>It is small. It is blue. You use it to write. → It is a pen!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Learning Profile</div><div class="ad">Students fill in a learning profile: "I study English because… I find ___ difficult/easy. I practise by… My homework is…" Integrates present simple (U5) + because (U13 Part 2 preview) + frequency adverbs (U5).</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Imperatives Full System · Can for Requests · How Questions</div><div class="lesson-sub">Do this! / Do not do that! · Can you…? for classroom requests · How do you…? / What does…?</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–12</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">imperatives (U8) — already introduced</span><span class="vr">can/can't (U7)</span><span class="vr">Wh- questions: What/Where/How (U2)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Imperatives — Positive and Negative (full system)</div><div class="ge">['Listen carefully. / Repeat after me. / Open your book.', 'Do not speak in your L1. / Do not write in pencil. / Do not forget your homework.', 'Please sit down. (Please makes it more polite)', "Let's work in pairs. (Let's from Unit 18 — preview)"]</div><div class="ex">P</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">m</div><div cla