div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">f</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">.</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">E</div><div class="ex">x</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">f</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">U</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">7</div><div class="ex">.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">How Questions — Learning Context</div><div class="ge">['How do you say "ciao" in English? — You say "hello" or "bye".', 'How do you spell "beautiful"? — B-E-A-U-T-I-F-U-L.', 'What does "improve" mean? — It means "to get better".', 'How do you pronounce this word?']</div><div class="ex">H</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">w</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">y</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">+</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">v</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">b</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">k</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">b</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">c</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">.</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">W</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">+</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">+</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">k</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">b</div><div class="ex">o</div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Classroom Request Role-Play</div><div class="ad">Students practise being both teacher and student. They must use: Can you…? / Can I…? / How do you…? / What does…? — all within a simulated lesson.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Positive to Negative</div><div class="ad">Teacher says a positive imperative. Students immediately say the negative. Forces both forms of the imperative.</div><div class=ap>Write in pencil! → Do not write in pencil! / Speak quietly! → Do not speak quietly — speak loudly!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Talk About Your Learning</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: Units 1–13 · Imperatives · Can for requests · Learning vocabulary</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–13</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">all prior grammar</span><span class="vr">classroom objects</span><span class="vr">learning verbs</span><span class="vr">can for requests</span><span class="vr">imperatives</span><span class="vr">how/what questions</span><span class="vr">study vocabulary</span><span class="vr">learning adjectives</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Perfect Language Class</div><div class="ad">Students describe their ideal language class using: imperatives (what the teacher does) + can you (what students can ask) + present simple (what happens every lesson) + adjectives (what the classroom is like).</div><div class=ap>"In my perfect class the teacher speaks slowly and explains everything clearly. Students can ask questions at any time. The lessons are interesting and useful. We do not have boring exercises — we always practise speaking!"</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Learning Tips Exchange</div><div class="ad">Students share their best tips for learning English using: I always… / I sometimes… / You should… / Can you try…? / It is useful to…</div><div class=ap>I always repeat new words 10 times. You should write words in a notebook. Can you try watching films in English? It is very useful!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">A Typical Lesson</div><div class="ad">Students describe what happens in a typical English lesson using all classroom vocabulary + present simple + frequency adverbs + imperatives.</div><div class=ap>The teacher says "Open your books." We repeat new words. We always work in pairs. Sometimes we have a test. I find speaking easy but writing is difficult.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Mind Matters</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: How do you learn best? What helps your brain? · Units 1–13 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#129504; MIND MATTERS — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">How do you learn best? What strategies help your memory and your language learning?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Give the class one learning tip using an imperative." Every student must give a different tip. Imperatives + classroom vocabulary activated in 2 minutes.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> How do you study? Do you find English easy or difficult? What do you do when you do not understand something? "I always write new words in a notebook. I repeat them every morning. When I do not understand I ask: Can you explain that again?"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher checks can for requests vs can for ability. "Can you swim?" (ability) vs "Can you repeat that?" (request) — the same word, two uses.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Describe how you learn English — your routine, your methods, what is easy, what is difficult, what you are going to do to improve. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Units 1–13: imperatives + can (ability/request) + present simple + how questions + all vocabulary active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 13 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–13</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Label 8 classroom objects from pictures</div><div class=ei>Match learning verbs to definitions: study / practise / revise / remember / forget / improve</div><div class=ei>Choose: easy / difficult / interesting / boring / useful for 4 situations</div><div class=ei>Write the correct classroom instruction for 4 situations</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write the negative imperative for 5 positive instructions</div><div class=ei>Complete classroom requests using Can you / Can I: 4 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write How do you / What does questions for 4 given answers</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 sentences mixing imperative + can + how question errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Give 3 learning tips using imperatives and should — 60 seconds</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 4 classroom questions using can you / how do you / what does</div><div class=ei>Describe how you study English — 2 min using present simple + frequency adverbs + learning vocabulary</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph about your English learning (8–10 sentences). Must include: imperatives (×2) · Can you/Can I (×2) · how do you / what does (×1 each) · present simple (×3) · at least 3 classroom/learning vocabulary items.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(11)">&#8592; Unit 12</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(13)">Unit 14 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-13"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 14 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 1</div><span class="part-badge part1-badge">&#127807; Part 1 — Essentials</span><div class="unit-title">Pets &amp; Animals</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to talk about animals — pets, farm animals and wildlife. Present simple third person is consolidated through animal habits. This is also the <strong>Part 1 final unit</strong> — the exam includes a full Part 1 review across all 14 units.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:47%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> present simple (U5) · have got (U3) · adjectives (U4) · prepositions of place (U7) · can/can't (U7) · all Part 1 grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Pets &amp; Animals</div><div class="lesson-sub">Common pets · Farm animals · Wild animals · Animal actions · Describing animals</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–13</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">have got (U3) — I have got a dog</span><span class="vr">am/is/are (U1)</span><span class="vr">adjectives (U4)</span><span class="vr">physical appearance (U12) — describing animals</span><span class="vr">present simple (U5) — habits of animals</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">dog / cat / rabbit / hamster / fish / bird / parrot / turtle</div><div class="vd">common pets</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">cow / horse / pig / sheep / chicken / duck / goat</div><div class="vd">farm animals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">lion / tiger / elephant / bear / wolf / fox / deer / monkey / snake</div><div class="vd">wild animals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bark / meow / roar / chirp / hiss / growl</div><div class="vd">animal sounds</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">run / jump / swim / fly / climb / hunt / sleep / eat</div><div class="vd">animal actions — present simple</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">fur / feathers / scales / tail / paws / wings / claws / beak</div><div class="vd">animal features — have got</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">wild / domestic / dangerous / friendly / gentle / aggressive / scared</div><div class="vd">animal adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">big / small / fast / slow / strong / intelligent / loyal</div><div class="vd">describing animals — recycles adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I have got a pet. / My pet is called… / I love animals.</div><div class="vd">pet ownership phrases</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Do you have a pet? / What animal do you prefer?</div><div class="vd">pet questions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Animal Description Challenge</div><div class="ad">Students describe an animal without saying its name. Others guess. Must use: have got (features) + present simple (habits) + adjectives (appearance).</div><div class=ap>It is big. It has got four legs and a long tail. It is orange and black. It is a wild animal. It hunts at night. It is very dangerous. → A tiger!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Pet Owner Survey</div><div class="ad">Mingle: students ask each other about pets using have got and present simple.</div><div class=ap>Have you got a pet? — Yes, I have got a cat. / What is it called? — It is called Luna. / Does it sleep a lot? — Yes, it always sleeps on my bed!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Dream Pet</div><div class="ad">Students describe their ideal pet using: have got + adjectives + present simple + because. Integrates all prior vocabulary.</div><div class=ap>My dream pet is a dog because dogs are very loyal and friendly. It has got soft fur and big brown eyes. It runs fast and it loves to swim.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Present Simple for Animal Habits · Have Got for Features · Prepositions of Place Review</div><div class="lesson-sub">Animals always / usually / never… · It has got… · The cat is on / under / behind the sofa</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Units 1–13</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">present simple (U5) — third person -s</span><span class="vr">have got (U3)</span><span class="vr">frequency adverbs (U5)</span><span class="vr">prepositions of place (U7)</span><span class="vr">there is/there are (U4)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Present Simple for Animal Habits — Third Person Review</div><div class="ge">['A dog barks. / A cat sleeps a lot. / A lion hunts at night.', 'Dogs always run fast. / Cats usually sleep 16 hours a day!', 'A parrot does not fly long distances. / Hamsters do not go outside.', 'Does your dog eat everything? — Yes, it does! / No, it does not.']</div><div class="ex">A</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">m</div><div class="ex">a</div><div class="ex">l</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">u</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">/</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">/</div><div class="ex"