a</div><div class="ex">r</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">p</div><div class="ex">e</div><div class="ex">t</div><div class="ex">s</div><div class="ex"> </div><div class="ex">h</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">d</div><div class="ex">i</div><div class="ex">n</div><div class="ex">g</div><div class="ex">?</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Animal True/False</div><div class="ad">Teacher makes statements about animals using present simple + have got. Students signal True or False and correct the false ones.</div><div class=ap>A dog has got feathers. → FALSE! A dog has got fur! / Lions always sleep after hunting. → TRUE! They sleep up to 20 hours a day!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Where is the Cat?</div><div class="ad">Picture of a room with animals in different positions. Students describe using prepositions + there is/there are + have got.</div><div class=ap>There is a dog behind the sofa. It has got a red collar. The cat is on the table next to the window.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Talk About Animals &amp; Pets</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: Units 1–14 · have got · present simple · adjectives · prepositions · nationalities</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–14</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">all prior grammar</span><span class="vr">animals vocabulary</span><span class="vr">animal sounds/actions</span><span class="vr">have got for features</span><span class="vr">present simple for habits</span><span class="vr">prepositions of place</span><span class="vr">frequency adverbs</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Animal Expert Panel</div><div class="ad">Each student becomes an expert on one animal. They present for 90 seconds using: It has got… / It usually… / It can… / It lives in… / It eats… — forces integration of have got + present simple + can + there is/there are.</div><div class=ap>"The elephant is the largest land animal. It has got big ears and a long trunk. It lives in Africa and Asia. It can swim but it cannot fly. It usually eats grass and fruit. Elephants are very intelligent — they are more intelligent than dogs!"</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Pet Routine</div><div class="ad">Students who have pets describe their pet's daily routine using full present simple + frequency adverbs + times from Unit 2.</div><div class=ap>"My cat wakes up at 6 in the morning. She always meows outside my bedroom door. She eats twice a day. In the evening she usually sits on the sofa next to me. She has got green eyes and white fur. She is 7 years old."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Would You Rather?</div><div class="ad">Students choose between animals and explain why using because + comparatives (U16 preview).</div><div class=ap>Would you rather have a dog or a cat? — I prefer dogs because they are more loyal than cats. A dog is also more active — it is good for your health!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With &amp; Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Life with and without a pet · Full Units 1–14 Part 1 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Life with and without a pet — how does an animal change your daily life?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Name one animal and say three facts about it using have got and present simple." — full Part 1 grammar activated in 60 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Do you have a pet? Would you like one? How does a pet change a person's daily routine? "My dog wakes me up at 7 every morning. I walk him for 30 minutes before breakfast. My life is very different because of him — I am more active and I feel less lonely."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Full Part 1 grammar audit — teacher tracks which students are integrating all grammar points (to be / have got / present simple / can / there is/are / imperatives) naturally in speech.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 3 min — PART 1 FINAL CHALLENGE:</strong> "Describe your home, your family, your daily routine, your appearance, something you have got, and an animal you like or have. Use everything from Part 1. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; FULL Part 1 spiral: all 14 grammar points active. Teacher produces personalised gap notes for each student before Part 2 begins.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 14 Assessment &amp; Part 1 Final Review</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–14 · A1 Part 1 Complete</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam — Part 1 Final Assessment</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (15 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write 6 pets and 6 wild animals from pictures</div><div class=ei>Match animal features to animals: fur / feathers / scales / wings / claws / beak</div><div class=ei>Write animal actions: bark / meow / roar / fly / swim / hunt</div><div class=ei>PART 1 REVIEW: label 10 mixed items from all 14 unit topics from pictures</div><div class=ei>Fill 5 gap sentences using vocabulary from any Part 1 unit</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (15 marks)</div><div class=ei>Present simple third person: write the correct form for 8 animal habit sentences</div><div class=ei>Have got: write 4 animal feature sentences from pictures</div><div class=ei>Prepositions: describe where 4 animals are in a room picture</div><div class=ei>PART 1 REVIEW: 10-way grammar discrimination — choose the correct form from all Part 1 grammar points</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 6 sentences — one error each, covering all 14 units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your favourite animal — 90 seconds using have got + present simple + adjectives</div><div class=ei>Answer 5 spontaneous questions covering any Part 1 topic</div><div class=ei>PART 1 FINAL SPEAK: "Tell me about yourself, your family, your home and your daily life." — 3 minutes. All Part 1 grammar must appear.</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph about an animal you like or have (8–10 sentences). Must include: have got (×3) · present simple (×3) · adjectives (×3) · a preposition of place · a frequency adverb. This piece is kept as evidence of A1 Part 1 completion.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(12)">&#8592; Unit 13</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(14)">Unit 15 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-14"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 24 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Prepositions of Time</div><div class="unit-desc">Students formally learn the three core time prepositions — <em>at</em>, <em>on</em>, <em>in</em> — plus connectors before/after/during/until. These appear in every topic and every tense, so mastering them transforms all prior and future language production.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:80%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> clock times (U11) · days/months/seasons · daily routine (U5) · going to (U18) · simple past (U28–U29) · all prior grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Time Prepositions in Context</div><div class="lesson-sub">at / on / in with time · common time phrases · exceptions</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">clock times (U11)</span><span class="vr">days of week (U5)</span><span class="vr">months/seasons (U16)</span><span class="vr">daily routine (U5)</span><span class="vr">numbers for years (U2)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">at 7 o'clock / at noon / at midnight / at night</div><div class="vd">at + specific time</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">at the weekend / at Christmas / at Easter / at the moment</div><div class="vd">at + special times</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">on Monday / on Tuesday… / on weekdays / on weekends</div><div class="vd">on + days</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">on 3rd March / on my birthday / on New Year's Day</div><div class="vd">on + dates and special days</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">in t