v><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Fill the Preposition</div><div class="ad">20 sentences with missing time prepositions. Students fill at/on/in/before/after/during/until.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Detective</div><div class="ad">10 sentences with wrong prepositions. Students find and correct each error. All common exception points included.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Describe Your Time</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · at/on/in · daily routine · plans · past experiences</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">at/on/in + all time vocabulary</span><span class="vr">daily routine (U5)</span><span class="vr">days/months/seasons</span><span class="vr">going to (U18)</span><span class="vr">simple past (U28-U29)</span><span class="vr">present simple (U5)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Time Interview</div><div class="ad">Pairs interview each other. Every question and answer must contain a time preposition.</div><div class=ap>When do you wake up? — At 7 on weekdays but at 9 at the weekend! / When did you start learning English? — In 2022. / What do you usually do in the evening? — At about 8 I watch a series.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Perfect Day</div><div class="ad">Students plan and describe their perfect day using at/on/in throughout. Must include morning/afternoon/evening + specific times.</div><div class=ap>On a perfect Saturday I wake up at 9. In the morning I have a long breakfast. At noon I go for a walk in the park. In the afternoon I...</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">When Did It Happen?</div><div class="ad">Students share 3 important life moments using past simple + time prepositions.</div><div class=ap>I was born in 1990. In 2015 I moved to France. On my first day at work I was very nervous. At the weekend I always called my family.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Keeping Up with Science</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: How does time affect us? · Units 15–24 + Part 1 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128270; KEEPING UP WITH SCIENCE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">How does time affect us? Sleep cycles, body clocks, and the psychology of time.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Describe your daily schedule using at/on/in for every single time reference." — time prepositions activated in 60 seconds under real pressure.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Are you a morning or evening person? Do you sleep at the right times? "In the morning I feel terrible but at night I have a lot of energy. On weekdays I wake up at 6 but at the weekend I sleep until noon. During work I drink 4 coffees!"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher collects at/on/in errors — especially in the morning vs at the morning (very common). Board all corrections.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Describe your ideal daily schedule from morning until night using at/on/in for every time reference. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; at/on/in + before/after/during/until now fully active alongside all prior grammar. Time is now precisely expressible.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 24 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–24</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Choose at/on/in for 15 time expressions</div><div class=ei>Write the correct time preposition for 5 sentences about routines</div><div class=ei>Fill: before/after/during/until in 4 sentences</div><div class=ei>Identify and correct 4 time preposition errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 8 sentences with the correct time preposition</div><div class=ei>Rewrite 4 sentences using a different time connector (before→after, during→until)</div><div class=ei>Write 4 complete sentences about your routine using at/on/in</div><div class=ei>Discrimination: 6 sentences — choose the correct preposition from context</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your weekly routine using at/on/in correctly throughout — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Answer 5 questions about time: "When do you…? / At what time…? / In which month…?"</div><div class=ei>Describe 3 important past moments using past simple + time prepositions</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph about your daily and weekly routine (8–10 sentences). Every sentence must contain a time preposition (at/on/in/before/after/during/until). Must also include present simple + going to + one past reference.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(13)">&#8592; Unit 14</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(15)">Unit 15 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-15"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 25 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Linking Words &amp; Connectors</div><div class="unit-desc">Students formally learn all essential English connectors — and/but/or/so/because/when/although and sequence words. This transforms all prior language production: students can now build complex, multi-clause sentences across all topics and tenses.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:83%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> because (U17) · before/after/during (U24) · all tenses · all vocabulary domains — connectors work with everything</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Linking Words &amp; Connectors</div><div class="lesson-sub">and · but · or · so · because · when · before · after · also · however</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">because (U17)</span><span class="vr">before/after (U24)</span><span class="vr">present simple (U5)</span><span class="vr">going to (U18)</span><span class="vr">simple past (U28–U29)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">and</div><div class="vd">addition — joins two similar ideas</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">but</div><div class="vd">contrast — joins two different ideas</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">or</div><div class="vd">alternative — gives a choice</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">so</div><div class="vd">result — the second idea is the result of the first</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">because</div><div class="vd">reason — explains why (already taught, now consolidated)</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">when</div><div class="vd">time — something happens at that moment</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">although / even though</div><div class="vd">unexpected contrast — stronger than but</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">also / too / as well</div><div class="vd">addition in a sentence or at the end</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">first / then / next / after that / finally</div><div class="vd">sequence connectors for storytelling</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">for example / such as</div><div class="vd">giving examples</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Sentence Completion Race</div><div class="ad">Students race to complete sentences using the correct connector. First to finish with all correct wins.</div><div class=ap>I like coffee ___ I do not like tea. (but) / I was tired ___ I went to bed early. (so) / She speaks French ___ Italian. (and)</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Connector Auction</div><div class="ad">Teams bid on sentences — correct connector use wins points. Forces discussion of which connector fits.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Connectors in Detail · Sentence Position · Punctuation</div><div class="lesson-sub">and/but/or/so at the start or middle · because mid-sentence · First…then…finally for stories</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">And / But / Or / So — coordinating connectors</div><div class="ge">['I like cats and I have got two at home.', 'She wants to go out but she is very tired.', 'Do you want coffee or tea? / I do not like coffee or tea — I prefer water!', 'It was raining so I stayed at home. (so = therefore/result)']</div><div class=ex>T</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>j</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>w</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>T</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>w</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>(</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex>)</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Because — subordinating connector</div><div class="ge">['I am tired because I did not sleep well. (middle)', 'Because I did not sleep well, I am tired. (start — note the comma)', 'She is happy because it is sunny and warm. (because + and combined)']</div><div class=ex>B</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>x</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>I<