ss=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>E</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Although / Even Though — unexpected contrast</div><div class="ge">['Although it was raining, I went for a walk.', 'She passed the exam even though she did not study much.', 'I like him although he is sometimes annoying!']</div><div class=ex>S</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>g</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>g</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>F</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>A</div><div class=ex>1</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>P</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>2</div><div class=ex>.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Connector Substitution</div><div class="ad">Students replace simple connectors with more advanced ones.</div><div class=ap>I was tired. I went to bed. → I was tired so I went to bed. / Although I was tired, I kept studying.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Story Builder</div><div class="ad">Students build a 6-sentence story using: First / Then / Next / After that / Finally + one although or even though.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Connect Your Ideas</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · All connectors · Longer, more complex sentences</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">and/but/or/so/because/when/although</span><span class="vr">first/then/next/finally</span><span class="vr">all prior grammar</span><span class="vr">present simple + past + going to</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">No Short Sentences!</div><div class="ad">Rule: every sentence must contain at least one connector. Students describe their day — no sentence can stand alone.</div><div class=ap>I wake up at 7 and then I have a shower. After that I have breakfast because I am always hungry in the morning. Although I do not like getting up early, I feel better after coffee!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">But Why?</div><div class="ad">Students make a statement. Partner asks "But why?" Students must answer using because or so. Repeats 5 times.</div><div class=ap>I do not eat meat. — But why? — Because I love animals and I think it is better for my health. — So what do you eat instead? — I eat vegetables, fish and a lot of pasta!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Tell Me a Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a 3-min story about something that happened using all sequence connectors + at least 3 other connector types.</div><div class=ap>First I was in Rome. Then I met a very interesting person. Although my Italian was not perfect, we talked for 3 hours. After that we had dinner. Finally we exchanged numbers and now we are good friends!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Debatable &amp; Relatable</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Is it better to plan or be spontaneous? · Full Part 2 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128293; DEBATABLE &amp; RELATABLE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Planning vs spontaneity — which leads to a better life?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Connect these two ideas using a different connector each time: 'I like to plan' + 'surprises are fun'." — and/but/or/so/although all tested in 60 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Do you prefer to plan or be spontaneous? Give reasons with because, contrast with but/although, add examples with also. "I love making plans because I feel more relaxed. But sometimes plans go wrong so you need to be flexible. Although I like structure, I also enjoy surprises!"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher collects sentences from students. Highlights how connectors transform simple sentences into rich, connected speech. Boards the most impressive examples.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Argue your position — planning or spontaneity. Use every connector type at least once. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; All connectors fully active. Students can now build complex, connected arguments. A major leap in fluency.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 25 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–25</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Match 8 connectors to their function: addition/contrast/reason/result/sequence</div><div class=ei>Choose the correct connector for 10 sentences</div><div class=ei>Rewrite 4 sentences using a different but similar connector</div><div class=ei>Identify 4 connector errors in sentences</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Join 8 pairs of sentences using the most appropriate connector</div><div class=ei>Add first/then/next/after that/finally to sequence a 5-step story</div><div class=ei>Rewrite 3 but sentences using although</div><div class=ei>Write 4 sentences about yourself — each must use a different connector</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your daily routine connecting all actions with sequence words — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Give your opinion on a topic using because/although/so/but — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Tell a short story about a past experience using all connector types — 2 min</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph of 8–10 connected sentences arguing a position (e.g. city vs countryside, morning vs evening person). Every sentence must contain at least one connector. Must include: and/but/so/because (×1 each) · although or even though (×1) · first/then/finally sequence (×1).</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(14)">&#8592; Unit 24</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(16)">Unit 26 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-16"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 26 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Object Pronouns &amp; Question Words</div><div class="unit-desc">The complete object pronoun set (me/him/her/it/us/them) and the full English question word inventory are formally taught. This completes the pronoun system and gives students every tool needed to ask and answer questions across all topics and tenses.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:87%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> subject pronouns (U1) · possessives (U3) · all question types from prior units · all tenses · all vocabulary</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Object Pronouns &amp; Full Question Word Set</div><div class="lesson-sub">me/you/him/her/it/us/them · Who/What/Where/When/Why/How/Which/How much/How many/How long/How often</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">subject pronouns (U1)</span><span class="vr">Wh- questions (U2)</span><span class="vr">possessives (U3)</span><span class="vr">do/does questions (U5)</span><span class="vr">can questions (U7)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">me / you / him / her / it / us / them</div><div class="vd">object pronouns — complete set</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Who…?</div><div class="vd">asking about a person</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What…?</div><div class="vd">asking about a thing or action</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Where…?</div><div class="vd">asking about a place</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">When…?</div><div class="vd">asking about time</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Why…?</div><div class="vd">asking about reason → answered with because</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How…?</div><div class="vd">asking about manner or method</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Which…?</div><div class="vd">asking for a choice between options</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How much…?</div><div class="vd">asking about quantity (uncountable) or price</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How many…?</div><div class="vd">asking about quantity (countable)</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How long…?</div><div class="vd">asking about duration</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How often…?</div><div class="vd">asking about frequency</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Question Word Match</div><div class="ad">12 answers on cards. Students write the correct question word for each answer.</div><div class=ap>"Three times a week." → How often? / "Because I love it." → Why? / "My sister." → Who? / "By bus." → How?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Object Pronoun Swap</div><div class="ad">Teacher says a sentence. Students replace the object noun with the correct pronoun.</div><div class=ap>"I like Maria." → I like her. / "He is reading the book." → He is reading it. / "We visited my parents." → We visited them.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Object Pronouns · Question Words in Depth · Indirect Questions</div><div class="lesson-sub">Give it to me · Who did you see? · How often do you…? · What time is it?</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Object Pronouns — the full system</div><div class="ge">['I like her. / She knows him. / Can you help me?', 'He gave it to us. / I sent them an email. / She is talking to you!', 'I → me / you → you / he → him / she → her / it → it / we → us / they → them', 'Give me the book! / Tell her the truth. / Can you hear us?']</div><div class=ex>O</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>j</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>j</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>T</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>A</div><div class=ex>F</div><div class=ex>T</div><div class=ex>E</div><div class=ex>R</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>C</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div 