div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>w</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex>j</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>k</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>q</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Question Formation Marathon</div><div class="ad">Students see an answer. They must write 3 different questions using 3 different question words that could produce that answer.</div><div class=ap>"At 8 o'clock." → When do you wake up? / What time does the lesson start? / How often do you eat at 8?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Object Pronoun Chain</div><div class="ad">Sentences get passed around. Each student replaces one noun with the correct object pronoun until all nouns are replaced.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Ask Everything, Replace Everything</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · All question words · Object pronouns · Natural conversation</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">who/what/where/when/why/how/which/how much/how many/how long/how often</span><span class="vr">me/you/him/her/it/us/them</span><span class="vr">all tenses</span><span class="vr">all vocabulary domains</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">20 Questions — Advanced</div><div class="ad">Classic game but students MUST use a different question word for each of their 20 questions. Covers the full question word set in one activity.</div><div class=ap>Is it a person? (who) / Where does it live? / How big is it? / What does it eat? / How long does it live? / Which country is it from? / How many legs has it got?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Replace Everything</div><div class="ad">Students tell a story. Partner retells it replacing ALL object nouns with pronouns. Tests whether both speakers track pronouns correctly.</div><div class=ap>"I met Ana yesterday. I gave Ana a book and Ana was very happy." → "I met her yesterday. I gave her a book and she was very happy!"</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Journalist</div><div class="ad">One student is a journalist. They must ask 10 questions about a topic using 10 DIFFERENT question words. The other student answers fully.</div><div class=ap>Who do you live with? / What do you do at the weekend? / Where did you grow up? / When did you start learning English? / Why? / How do you study? / Which do you prefer — speaking or writing? / How long have you studied? / How often do you practise? / How well do you speak now?</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With &amp; Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Life with and without questions — curiosity as a superpower · Full Part 2 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Life with and without curiosity — do questions make you a better learner and person?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Ask the person next to you 5 questions in 60 seconds using 5 different question words." — entire question word set activated under time pressure.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Are you a curious person? How often do you ask questions? Why is asking questions important for learning a language? Who do you ask when you do not understand something?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher checks object pronoun accuracy — him vs her, us vs them confusions are very common. Also checks how much vs how many (U6 recycled).</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Ask me anything and then answer your own questions. Use at least 8 different question words and replace all object nouns with pronouns. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Complete question word set + object pronouns now active. Natural conversation is now fully possible at A1.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 26 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–26</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Match 10 question words to the type of information they ask about</div><div class=ei>Write the correct object pronoun for 8 underlined nouns in sentences</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 questions using the correct question word from context</div><div class=ei>Write questions for 4 given answers using the correct question word</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Replace all object nouns with pronouns in 6 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write 8 complete questions using different question words — all tenses</div><div class=ei>Choose: How much or How many for 6 sentences</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 object pronoun errors + 2 wrong question words</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Interview the examiner using 8 different question words — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Retell a story replacing all object nouns with pronouns — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Answer 5 questions with full sentences including object pronouns throughout</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a dialogue of 10 exchanges (question + answer). Must include: 8 different question words · object pronouns in every answer · at least 3 different tenses · connectors (and/but/because) in answers.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(15)">&#8592; Unit 25</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(17)">Unit 28 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-17"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 27 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Technology &amp; Communication</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to talk about digital life — devices, apps, social media and online habits. This is essential modern A1 vocabulary. <em>Use + noun + to + infinitive</em> is introduced as a highly productive grammar structure. The unit brings all prior grammar into a contemporary everyday context.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:90%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> present simple (U5) · can/can't (U7) · how long/how often (U26) · connectors (U25) · going to (U18) · all prior grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Technology &amp; Communication</div><div class="lesson-sub">Devices · Apps · Internet · Social media · Digital actions · Communication verbs</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">present simple (U5)</span><span class="vr">can/can't (U7)</span><span class="vr">have got (U3)</span><span class="vr">going to (U18)</span><span class="vr">simple past (U28–U29)</span><span class="vr">question words (U26)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">phone / smartphone / laptop / tablet / computer</div><div class="vd">devices</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">screen / keyboard / camera / battery / charger / headphones</div><div class="vd">device parts</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">internet / Wi-Fi / app / website / browser / search engine</div><div class="vd">internet basics</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">email / message / text / call / video call / voicemail</div><div class="vd">communication types</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">social media / Instagram / WhatsApp / YouTube</div><div class="vd">social platforms</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">send / receive / download / upload / search / click / scroll / swipe</div><div class="vd">digital actions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">post / like / share / follow / comment / block / delete</div><div class="vd">social media actions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">password / username / profile / account / notification</div><div class="vd">account vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">online / offline / connected / disconnected</div><div class="vd">connection status</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I use my phone to… / I spend ___ hours on my phone.</div><div class="vd">usage expressions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Tech in My Life</div><div class="ad">Students describe how they use technology daily — forced integration of present simple (U5) + frequency adverbs (U5) + how long (U26).</div><div class=ap>I use my phone about 4 hours a day. I always check my messages in the morning. I never use my phone during meals. I send about 50 messages every day!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">App Recommendation</div><div class="ad">Students recommend an app to the class using: You should… / You can… / It is useful because…</div><div class=ap>You should download this app. You can use it to practise English. It is free and it sends you notifications every day. I have been using it for 6 months and my vocabulary has improved a lot!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Present Simple for Digital Habits · Can for Technology · How Long / How Often</div><div class="lesson-sub">I use my phone to… · You can download it. · How long do you spend online?</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Use + noun + to + infinitive</div><div class="ge">['I use my laptop to work. / She uses her phone to listen to music.', 'We use WhatsApp to communicate with our family.', 'He uses a dictionary app to learn new words.', 'What do you use your phone for? / What do you use it to do?']</div><div class=ex>D</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>g</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>C</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>w</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Can for Technology — ability and possibility</div><div class="ge">['You can download it for free. / Can I use your charger?', 'You cannot use your phone during the exam.', 'With this app you can practise your pronunciation.', 'I cannot connect — I have not got Wi-Fi here.']</div><div class=ex>E</div><div class=ex>x</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>U</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>7</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>g</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">How Long / How Much Time + Spend</div><div class="ge">['How long do you spend on your phone every day?', 'I spend about 3 hours a day on social media.', 'How much time does she spend watching videos? — Too much!', 'He spends his evenings browsing the internet.']</div><div class=ex>E</div><div class=ex>x</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex>u</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>f</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>a</div><div class=ex>c</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>y</div><div class=ex>.</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>C</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>m</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>w</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>l</div><div class=ex>o</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>g</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>(</div><div class=ex>U</div><div class=ex>2</div><div class=ex>6</div><div class=ex>)</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>w</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>t</div><div class=ex>h</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>s</div><div class=ex>p</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>d</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>+</div><div class=ex> </div><div class=ex>v</div><div class=ex>e</div><div class=ex>r</div><div class=ex>b</div><div class=ex>-</div><div class=ex>i</div><div class=ex>n</div><div class=ex>g</div><div class=ex>.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Digital Day</div><div class="ad">Students describe their digital habits using use + to + infinitive + how long.</div><div class=ap>I wake up and immediately check my phone. I use it to read the news. Then I use my laptop to work. I spend about 2 hours on email. In the evening I use my phone to watch videos — usually about an hour.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Tech Q&A</div><div class="ad">Students interview each other about technology habits using all question words from U26.</div><div class=ap>How often do you check social media? / What do you use your laptop for? / How long do you spend on your phone? / Why do you use WhatsApp? / Which app do you use most?</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Technology in Your Life</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · All technology vocabulary · Present simple · Can · How long/often · Connectors</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">all technology vocabulary</span><span class="vr">present simple (U5)</span><span class="vr">can/can't (U7)</span><span class="vr">how long/how often (U26)</span><span class="vr">connectors (U25)</span><span class="vr">going to (U18)</span><span class="vr">should (U16)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Digital Detox Debate</div><div class="ad">Should people spend less time on their phones? Students argue for or against using all connectors (U25) + because + should.</div><div class=ap>"I think people spend too much time on their phones because it is addictive. Although social media is useful for communication, it is bad for your mental health. People should put their phones down and talk to each other. However, without technology we cannot work or study efficiently!"</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Digital Life Profile</div><div class="ad">Students present their digital life: devices they have, apps they use, how long they spend, what they do online and what they are going to change.</div><div class=ap>"I have got a smartphone and a laptop. I use my phone about 5 hours a day — mainly for WhatsApp and Instagram. I also use it to listen to music while I exercise. I am going to spend less time on social media because it makes me feel stressed. I am going to use that time to practise English instead!"</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Teach Me the App</div><div class="ad">Students explain how to use an app using imperatives (U13) + can + you can/cannot.</div><div class=ap>"First, download the app. Then create an account — you need an email address and a password. After that, you can search for anything. You cannot post without an account but you can read everything for free."</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Debatable &amp; Relatable</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Is technology making us more or less human? · Full Part 2 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128293; DEBATABLE &amp; RELATABLE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Is technology making us more connected or more isolated?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "How many apps do you use every day? How long do you spend on your phone? Answer using how many/how long — question words from U26 activated immediately."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Is social media good or bad for relationships? Can technology replace human contact? Although we can communicate with anyone in the world, do we feel lonelier? Students use comparatives (U20) + although + because + connectors throughout.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher audits connector use — are students using although/even though or only but? Also checks object pronouns — do they say "I use it/them" or "I use the phone/the apps"?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 2 min:</strong> "Argue your position on technology — is it a blessing or a curse? Use connectors, comparatives, question words and object pronouns throughout. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; All Part 2 grammar active in one connected argument. Students demonstrate A1 Part 2 mastery.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 27 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–27</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Label 8 technology items from pictures</div><div class=ei>Match digital actions to definitions: send/download/upload/scroll/swipe/post/share</div><div class=ei>Fill 5 gap sentences with technology vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences about how you use technology using use + to + infinitive</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences with use/uses + noun + to + infinitive</div><div class=ei>Write can/cannot sentences about what you can do with 4 different apps</div><div class=ei>Answer: How long do you spend…? / How often do you…? — 4 questions with full sentences</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 use + to errors + 2 can errors + 2 object pronoun errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your digital life — devices, apps, habits, time spent — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Explain how to use one app step by step using imperatives + can — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Give your opinion on a technology topic using connectors + comparatives — 2 min</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph about technology in your life (8–10 sentences). Must include: use + to + infinitive (×3) · can/cannot (×2) · how long / how often reference · a connector (×3) · an object pronoun (×3) · going to for a future tech plan.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(16)">&#8592; Unit 17</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(18)">Unit 18 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-18"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 15 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Time &amp; Weather</div><div class="unit-desc">Students deepen their understanding of time expressions and learn to describe weather. Present continuous is fully introduced — the most important A1 Part 2 grammar distinction.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:50%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> ALL Part 1 grammar + vocabulary · present continuous preview from Unit 10</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Time &  Weather</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">ALL Part 1 grammar + vocabulary · present continuous preview from Unit 10</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What time is it? / At what time?</div><div class="vd">full clock questions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">midnight / noon / midday / dawn / dusk</div><div class="vd">precise time vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">five past / ten to / twenty-five past</div><div class="vd">full clock face</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">yesterday / today / tomorrow / this week / next week</div><div class="vd">time reference</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">sunny / cloudy / rainy / windy / foggy / snowy / stormy</div><div class="vd">weather adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">hot / warm / cool / cold / freezing / boiling</div><div class="vd">temperature scale</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What's the weather like? / It's raining. / It's snowing.</div><div class="vd">weather expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">spring / summer / autumn / winter</div><div class="vd">seasons preview</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Present Continuous — I am + verb-ing, Weather + It — special to be use</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Present Continuous — I am + verb-ing</div><div class="ge">For actions happening now or around now. KEY contrast: present simple = habit, present continuous = now.</div><div class="ex">I am studying English now. / She is watching TV at the moment.</div><div class="ex">I study English every day. (habit) vs I am studying right now. (now)</div><div class="ex">What are you doing? — I am reading. / He is not working today.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Weather + It — special to be use</div><div class="ge">It with weather and time — no real subject in meaning. Extends to be from Unit 1.</div><div class="ex">It is sunny today. / It is raining. / Is it cold outside? — Yes, it is.</div><div class="ex">It is 8 o clock. / What time is it? — It is quarter past nine.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Time &  Weather</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–11</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">ALL Part 1 grammar + vocabulary · present continuous preview from Unit 10 + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Time &  Weather to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128270; Keeping Up with Science · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128270; Keeping Up with Science</div><div class="st">How does weather affect our mood and productivity?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: What is the weather like today? How does it make you feel? — weather + feelings + to be instantly.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you prefer summer or winter? Does the weather affect what you do? "When it is raining I usually stay at home and read."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Present simple vs present continuous — the most important A1 Part 2 distinction. Board examples.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe the weather today and what you are doing. Then your perfect weather day. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Present continuous now fully active alongside present simple + all Part 1 grammar. Two present tenses available.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 11 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–23</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 11 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Time &  Weather using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(17)">&#8592; Unit 18</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(19)">Unit 19 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-19"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 16 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">The Body &amp; Health</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn body vocabulary and describe health problems. Should and should not are introduced as the first modal verbs — giving students the ability to give and receive advice.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:55%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> present continuous · present simple · to be · can · have got · all Part 1 vocabulary</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — The Body &  Health</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">present continuous · present simple · to be · can · have got · all Part 1 vocabulary</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">head / face / hair / eye / ear / nose / mouth / tooth / teeth</div><div class="vd">head and face</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">neck / shoulder / arm / elbow / hand / finger / thumb</div><div class="vd">upper body</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">chest / back / stomach / hip / leg / knee / foot / feet / toe</div><div class="vd">lower body</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">headache / stomachache / backache / toothache / sore throat</div><div class="vd">common pains</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I feel sick / tired / dizzy / better / worse</div><div class="vd">health feelings</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">cold / flu / fever / allergy / injury / rash</div><div class="vd">common illnesses</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">doctor / nurse / hospital / pharmacy / medicine / tablet / injection</div><div class="vd">medical vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">appointment / prescription / symptoms / treatment / recovery</div><div class="vd">medical process</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Should / Should not — advice and recommendations, Have a + illness — different from have got</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Should / Should not — advice and recommendations</div><div class="ge">First modal verb. Never changes form — no -s for third person. Followed by base verb.</div><div class="ex">You should drink more water. / She should see a doctor.</div><div class="ex">He should not work — he has a fever!</div><div class="ex">Should I take a tablet? — Yes, you should. / No, you should not.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Have a + illness — different from have got</div><div class="ge">Use have (not have got) for illnesses. Both forms are common but have is more natural here.</div><div class="ex">I have a headache. / She has a cold. / He has a temperature.</div><div class="ex">Do you have a sore throat? — Yes, I do. (present simple question)</div><div class="ex">I do not have a fever. / She does not have an allergy.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — The Body &  Health</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–12</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">present continuous · present simple · to be · can · have got · all Part 1 vocabulary + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect The Body &  Health to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#129504; Mind Matters · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#129504; Mind Matters</div><div class="st">The mind-body connection — how does your body feel when you are stressed?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Point to a part of your body and say one sentence about it. Body vocabulary activated immediately.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you get ill often? What do you do when you have a headache? Should people exercise every day?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Have a (illness) vs have got (possession) — a very common confusion. Board the contrast clearly.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe how you feel today — your body, energy, mood. Give advice to someone who is tired. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Should/should not now active alongside can + all Part 1 grammar. Advice and health vocabulary fully available.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 12 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–28</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 12 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on The Body &  Health using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(18)">&#8592; Unit 11</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(20)">Unit 13 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-20"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 17 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Feelings &amp; Moods</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to express emotions and describe moods with precision. Because introduces cause and effect. Intensifiers give students the ability to express degrees of feeling for the first time.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:59%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> should · present continuous · present simple · to be · can · have got · all Part 1</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Feelings &  Moods</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">should · present continuous · present simple · to be · can · have got · all Part 1</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">happy / sad / angry / scared / surprised / excited / bored / nervous</div><div class="vd">basic emotions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">tired / stressed / relaxed / confused / proud / ashamed / lonely</div><div class="vd">nuanced feelings</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">in a good mood / in a bad mood / feeling great / feeling awful</div><div class="vd">mood expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Why? / Because…</div><div class="vd">reason question and answer</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">very / really / quite / a bit / extremely / absolutely</div><div class="vd">intensifiers</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I feel… / I am feeling… / I look… / I seem…</div><div class="vd">feeling expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">It makes me feel… / It makes me happy / angry / tired</div><div class="vd">cause and effect</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Cheer up! / Calm down! / Do not worry!</div><div class="vd">expressions of comfort</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Look / Feel / Seem + adjective — Stative Verbs, Because — linking cause and reason</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Look / Feel / Seem + adjective — Stative Verbs</div><div class="ge">These verbs describe states not actions. They use present simple even for right now.</div><div class="ex">I feel happy today. / She looks tired. / He seems nervous.</div><div class="ex">You look great today! / It seems cold outside.</div><div class="ex">She is feeling tired. (also possible with feel in continuous)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Because — linking cause and reason</div><div class="ge">First connector at A1 Part 2. Simple but transforms sentence depth and coherence.</div><div class="ex">I am happy because it is sunny.</div><div class="ex">She is tired because she does not sleep well.</div><div class="ex">He should see a doctor because he has a fever. (should recycled)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Feelings &  Moods</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–13</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">should · present continuous · present simple · to be · can · have got · all Part 1 + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Feelings &  Moods to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#129504; Mind Matters · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#129504; Mind Matters</div><div class="st">Can you control your emotions? What makes you really happy?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Show an emotion with your face. Others guess: Are you happy? Do you feel nervous? — vocabulary activated immediately.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: What makes you happy? What makes you stressed? Should people talk about their feelings?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Stative verb errors — I am feeling vs I feel. Board both and explain when each works.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your mood right now and why. Then describe a time you felt very happy. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Because + stative verbs + intensifiers now active. Emotional depth and cause-effect available in all speaking tasks.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 13 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–29</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 13 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Feelings &  Moods using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(19)">&#8592; Unit 12</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(21)">Unit 14 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-21"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 18 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Hobbies &amp; Free Time</div><div class="unit-desc">Students talk about leisure activities and interests. Going to introduces the future dimension — the first future tense at A1. It immediately combines with all present tenses students know.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:64%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> because · stative verbs · should · present continuous · present simple · all Part 1</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Hobbies &  Free Time</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">because · stative verbs · should · present continuous · present simple · all Part 1</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">play sport / play football / tennis / basketball / chess</div><div class="vd">sports and games</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">play an instrument / guitar / piano / violin / drums</div><div class="vd">music hobbies</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">read books / magazines / comics / novels</div><div class="vd">reading</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">watch films / series / documentaries / news</div><div class="vd">screen time</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">cook / bake / paint / draw / photograph / knit</div><div class="vd">creative hobbies</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">go swimming / cycling / running / hiking / dancing / climbing</div><div class="vd">active hobbies</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">once a week / twice a month / every day / at the weekend / in my free time</div><div class="vd">frequency expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I enjoy… / I am interested in… / I am good at… / It is fun / relaxing / boring</div><div class="vd">interest and opinion expressions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Going To — future plans and intentions, Like / Love / Enjoy / Hate + verb-ing</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Going To — future plans and intentions</div><div class="ge">Use going to for plans already decided. Contrast with present simple (habit) and present continuous (now).</div><div class="ex">I am going to play tennis tomorrow.</div><div class="ex">Are you going to cook tonight? — Yes, I am. / No, I am not.</div><div class="ex">He is not going to watch TV — he is going to read.</div><div class="ex">I play tennis every week. (habit) vs I am going to play tennis tomorrow. (plan)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Like / Love / Enjoy / Hate + verb-ing</div><div class="ge">Verbs of preference take -ing. Contrast with would like + infinitive from Unit 9.</div><div class="ex">I like swimming. / She loves reading. / He enjoys cooking. / They hate waiting.</div><div class="ex">I would like to go swimming today. (specific now — would like + infinitive)</div><div class="ex">Do you enjoy watching films? — Yes, I love it!</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Hobbies &  Free Time</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–14</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">because · stative verbs · should · present continuous · present simple · all Part 1 + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Hobbies &  Free Time to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#9878;&#65039; My Life With and Without · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; My Life With and Without</div><div class="st">Life with and without your favourite hobby.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: What are you going to do at the weekend? — going to activated immediately in real context.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: What hobbies do you have? How often? Would you like to learn something new? "I enjoy cooking but I am going to start painting next month."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Going to vs present simple — plan vs habit. Board student examples.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your hobbies — what you like, how often, what you are going to do next weekend. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Going to + like/enjoy + verb-ing now active. Future reference available. All three present tenses + future now in use.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 14 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–30</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 14 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Hobbies &  Free Time using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(20)">&#8592; Unit 13</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(22)">Unit 15 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-22"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 19 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Jobs &amp; Workplaces</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to talk about professions and work routines. Adverbs of manner are introduced. Present continuous extends to temporary situations — a key distinction from permanent states.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:68%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> going to · because · like/enjoy + verb-ing · present continuous · present simple · all Part 1</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Jobs &  Workplaces</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">going to · because · like/enjoy + verb-ing · present continuous · present simple · all Part 1</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">doctor / nurse / teacher / engineer / lawyer / architect</div><div class="vd">professional jobs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">chef / waiter / driver / mechanic / farmer / builder</div><div class="vd">practical jobs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">artist / musician / writer / designer / photographer</div><div class="vd">creative jobs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">manager / director / assistant / accountant / receptionist</div><div class="vd">office jobs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">office / factory / hospital / school / studio / outdoors / from home</div><div class="vd">workplaces</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">work full-time / part-time / shifts / from home / freelance</div><div class="vd">work patterns</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What do you do? / I work as a… / I am a… / I am self-employed.</div><div class="vd">job questions and answers</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">stressful / rewarding / boring / creative / well-paid / challenging</div><div class="vd">job adjectives</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Adverbs of Manner — carefully / quickly / well, Present Continuous for Temporary Situations</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Adverbs of Manner — carefully / quickly / well</div><div class="ge">Adverbs modify how an action is done. Most adjectives add -ly. Good becomes well (irregular).</div><div class="ex">She works hard. / He speaks quietly. / They drive carefully.</div><div class="ex">Quick → quickly / Slow → slowly / Good → well (irregular!)</div><div class="ex">She is a good teacher. (adjective) / She teaches well. (adverb) — KEY CONTRAST</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Present Continuous for Temporary Situations</div><div class="ge">Extends present continuous to things true now but not permanent.</div><div class="ex">I usually work in an office but this week I am working from home.</div><div class="ex">She is a teacher but she is studying medicine at the moment.</div><div class="ex">They are not working today — it is a national holiday.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Jobs &  Workplaces</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–15</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">going to · because · like/enjoy + verb-ing · present continuous · present simple · all Part 1 + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Jobs &  Workplaces to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128293; Debatable and Relatable · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128293; Debatable and Relatable</div><div class="st">Is your job your identity? Can you separate work from who you are?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: What do you do? How do you feel about your job? — job vocabulary + stative verbs instantly.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you enjoy your work? Do you work hard? What is your dream job? Are you going to change careers?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Adjective vs adverb confusion — good vs well. Board the contrast and drill it.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your job — what you do, how you do it, what you are going to do next in your career. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Adverbs of manner + temporary present continuous now active alongside all prior grammar.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 15 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–23</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 15 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Jobs &  Workplaces using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(21)">&#8592; Unit 14</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(23)">Unit 16 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-23"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 20 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Seasons &amp; Nature</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn seasons, nature and environment. Comparative adjectives are introduced — warmer, colder, more beautiful. This transforms describing and comparing ability across all topics.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:73%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> adverbs · going to · present continuous · present simple · should · all Part 1 + Part 2</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Seasons &  Nature</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">adverbs · going to · present continuous · present simple · should · all Part 1 + Part 2</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">spring / summer / autumn / winter</div><div class="vd">seasons</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">mountain / river / lake / sea / ocean / beach / forest / desert / island</div><div class="vd">natural landscape</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">tree / flower / grass / leaf / rock / sand / sky / cloud / sun / moon</div><div class="vd">nature objects</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bird / fish / dog / cat / horse / bear / wolf / eagle</div><div class="vd">common animals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">weather in each season — snow in winter / flowers in spring</div><div class="vd">seasonal associations</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">environment: pollution / clean air / nature / countryside / city</div><div class="vd">environment vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I love / prefer / hate the summer because…</div><div class="vd">season preferences with because</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Comparative Adjectives — more / less / -er than, As … as — equal comparison</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Comparative Adjectives — more / less / -er than</div><div class="ge">Compare two things. Short adjectives add -er. Long adjectives use more. Always use than after the comparative.</div><div class="ex">Hot → hotter / Cold → colder / Big → bigger (double consonant)</div><div class="ex">Beautiful → more beautiful / Interesting → more interesting</div><div class="ex">Good → better / Bad → worse (irregular)</div><div class="ex">Summer is hotter than winter. / The countryside is more beautiful than the city.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">As … as — equal comparison</div><div class="ge">Express that two things are equal. Not as … as expresses inequality.</div><div class="ex">The beach is as beautiful as the mountains.</div><div class="ex">My city is not as clean as the countryside.</div><div class="ex">Is English as difficult as Russian? — No, it is not as hard!</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Seasons &  Nature</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–16</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">adverbs · going to · present continuous · present simple · should · all Part 1 + Part 2 + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Seasons &  Nature to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128270; Keeping Up with Science · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128270; Keeping Up with Science</div><div class="st">Climate change — is our planet getting warmer? What should we do?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Compare summer and winter in your country — which is better? Use comparatives immediately.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Is your city getting more polluted? Is the countryside more beautiful than the city? What should people do to protect nature?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Comparative formation errors — more hotter is very common. Board the rules clearly.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your favourite season and landscape. Compare it to another. Say what you are going to do next summer. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Comparative adjectives + as ... as now active. Comparing and contrasting fully possible across all topics.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 16 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–28</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 16 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Seasons &  Nature using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(22)">&#8592; Unit 15</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(24)">Unit 17 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-24"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 21 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Possessions &amp; Describing Objects</div><div class="unit-desc">Students describe objects in detail using colour, size, material and shape. Superlative adjectives complete the comparison system. Objects from all prior vocabulary are now fully describable.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:77%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> comparatives · going to · present continuous · present simple · adjectives · colours · all prior</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Possessions &  Describing Objects</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">comparatives · going to · present continuous · present simple · adjectives · colours · all prior</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">made of wood / metal / plastic / glass / leather / cotton / wool / silk</div><div class="vd">materials</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">round / square / rectangular / oval / long / short / wide / narrow / flat</div><div class="vd">shapes</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">heavy / light / hard / soft / rough / smooth / sharp / fragile</div><div class="vd">physical properties</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">old / new / ancient / modern / broken / working / second-hand / brand new</div><div class="vd">condition</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">valuable / worthless / rare / common / unique / precious</div><div class="vd">value adjectives</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What is it made of? / What does it look like? / What shape is it?</div><div class="vd">description questions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I use it for… / It belongs to… / It reminds me of…</div><div class="vd">function and personal meaning</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Superlative Adjectives — the most / the -est, Adjective Order — opinion / size / age / shape / colour / origin / material + noun</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Superlative Adjectives — the most / the -est</div><div class="ge">The extreme end of a group. Short adjectives add -est. Long adjectives use the most. Always use the.</div><div class="ex">Hot → the hottest / Cold → the coldest / Big → the biggest</div><div class="ex">Beautiful → the most beautiful / Expensive → the most expensive</div><div class="ex">Good → the best / Bad → the worst (irregular)</div><div class="ex">This is the most expensive restaurant in the city.</div><div class="ex">Summer is the best season. / Monday is the worst day of the week.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Adjective Order — opinion / size / age / shape / colour / origin / material + noun</div><div class="ge">Multiple adjectives follow this order. In practice 2-3 adjectives are enough.</div><div class="ex">a beautiful big old brown leather bag</div><div class="ex">a small new red plastic box / a nice old wooden table</div><div class="ex">The order feels natural when practised — errors feel wrong to native ears.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Possessions &  Describing Objects</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–17</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">comparatives · going to · present continuous · present simple · adjectives · colours · all prior + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Possessions &  Describing Objects to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128172; The Greatest Quotes · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128172; The Greatest Quotes</div><div class="st">A possession that means more than its price.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Describe one object you have with you right now using 3 adjectives and adjective order.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: What is your most valuable possession? What is it made of? What does it look like? Why is it the best thing you own?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Adjective order errors + superlative formation — most biggest is very common. Board both rules.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your 3 most important possessions — appearance, material, why they are the best. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Superlatives + adjective order now active alongside comparatives + all prior grammar. Full description possible.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 17 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–29</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 17 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Possessions &  Describing Objects using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(23)">&#8592; Unit 16</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(25)">Unit 18 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-25"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 22 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Making Plans &amp; Suggestions</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to make plans, suggest activities and accept or decline invitations. Let's and shall we introduce collaborative grammar. Present continuous for fixed future completes the future picture.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:82%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> superlatives · comparatives · going to · present continuous · all prior grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Making Plans &  Suggestions</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">superlatives · comparatives · going to · present continuous · all prior grammar</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Let's… / Shall we…? / Why don't we…? / How about…?</div><div class="vd">suggestion phrases</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">That's a great idea! / I'd love to! / Sounds good! / Perfect!</div><div class="vd">accepting suggestions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I'm sorry I can't. / Maybe another time. / I'd prefer not to.</div><div class="vd">declining politely</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Would you like to…? / Do you want to…? / Are you free…?</div><div class="vd">invitation phrases</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">this evening / tonight / tomorrow morning / next weekend / in the summer</div><div class="vd">future time expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">make a plan / arrange / cancel / postpone / confirm / reschedule</div><div class="vd">planning verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What are you doing on Saturday? / Are you busy? / Are you free?</div><div class="vd">checking availability</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Let's + base verb / Shall we + base verb?, Present Continuous for Fixed Future Plans</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Let's + base verb / Shall we + base verb?</div><div class="ge">Collaborative suggestions. No subject needed. Let's = let us (contracted).</div><div class="ex">Let's go to the cinema tonight. / Shall we have lunch together?</div><div class="ex">Let's not stay at home — let's go for a walk!</div><div class="ex">Shall we meet at the cafe near the station? (prepositions from Unit 7 recycled)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Present Continuous for Fixed Future Plans</div><div class="ge">When a plan is booked or arranged — it is in the diary. More certain than going to.</div><div class="ex">I am meeting Ana tomorrow morning. (fixed, already arranged)</div><div class="ex">She is flying to Paris next week. (ticket booked)</div><div class="ex">Going to = plan in mind. Present continuous = plan in the diary.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Making Plans &  Suggestions</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–18</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">superlatives · comparatives · going to · present continuous · all prior grammar + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Making Plans &  Suggestions to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128293; Debatable and Relatable · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128293; Debatable and Relatable</div><div class="st">Spontaneous plans vs organised plans — which is better?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Suggest something to do this weekend using Let's or Shall we. New grammar activated in 30 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you prefer to plan ahead or be spontaneous? Shall we make a plan right now? What are you doing next weekend?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Let's vs shall we vs going to — when to use which. Board the differences with examples.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your plans for the next week — what you are doing, who with, where, why. Use Let's and going to. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Let's + shall we + present continuous for future now active. Future reference is now rich and flexible.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 18 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–30</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 18 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Making Plans &  Suggestions using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(24)">&#8592; Unit 17</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(26)">Unit 19 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-26"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 23 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Likes, Dislikes &amp; Preferences</div><div class="unit-desc">Students express opinions, preferences and degrees of feeling with precision. So do I and neither do I enable real conversational agreement and disagreement — a landmark social skill.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:86%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> let's · shall we · going to · present continuous · present simple · all prior grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Likes, Dislikes &  Preferences</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">let's · shall we · going to · present continuous · present simple · all prior grammar</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I love / really like / quite like / do not mind / do not really like / hate</div><div class="vd">preference scale</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I prefer… to… / I would rather… than…</div><div class="vd">preference comparisons</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What do you think of…? / What is your opinion of…?</div><div class="vd">asking opinions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I think… / In my opinion… / I believe… / I feel that…</div><div class="vd">giving opinions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I agree / I disagree / I am not sure / That is true / I do not think so</div><div class="vd">agreeing and disagreeing</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">It depends. / It is hard to say. / Both are good. / I can see both sides.</div><div class="vd">hedging language</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">My favourite… is… / One of my favourite things is…</div><div class="vd">talking about favourites</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">So do I / Neither do I — conversational agreement, Verb + -ing vs Verb + infinitive — introduction</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">So do I / Neither do I — conversational agreement</div><div class="ge">So do I = me too (positive). Neither do I = me neither (negative). The auxiliary verb matches the original.</div><div class="ex">I love pizza. — So do I! / I do not like fish. — Neither do I.</div><div class="ex">She can swim. — So can I. / He has not got a car. — Neither have I.</div><div class="ex">I am going to Paris. — So am I! (auxiliary = am from going to)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Verb + -ing vs Verb + infinitive — introduction</div><div class="ge">Some verbs take -ing, others take to + infinitive. Previewed here, fully taught at A2.</div><div class="ex">I enjoy reading. / I love swimming. / I hate cooking. (enjoy/like/love/hate + -ing)</div><div class="ex">I want to go. / I would like to try. / I need to study. (want/would like/need + infinitive)</div><div class="ex">I like to cook. AND I like cooking. (like allows both)</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Likes, Dislikes &  Preferences</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–19</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">let's · shall we · going to · present continuous · present simple · all prior grammar + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Likes, Dislikes &  Preferences to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128293; Debatable and Relatable · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128293; Debatable and Relatable</div><div class="st">Social media — do you love it or hate it? Could you live without it?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Say one thing you love and one you hate. Partner responds: So do I / Neither do I. New grammar in 60 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: What do you think of social media? Do you prefer Instagram or real conversation? In your opinion should children use social media?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: So do I vs So am I vs So can I — auxiliary matching. Board student errors.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Give opinions on 3 topics — social media, city vs countryside, summer vs winter. Use I think, I prefer, so do I. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; So do I + neither do I + opinion language now active. Real conversational exchange now possible at A1.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 19 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–23</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 19 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Likes, Dislikes &  Preferences using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(25)">&#8592; Unit 18</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(27)">Unit 20 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-27"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 28 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Simple Past — Regular Verbs</div><div class="unit-desc">Students talk about completed past events. Simple past of regular verbs is the most significant new grammar point of A1 Part 2 — it adds a new time dimension to all topics covered so far.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:91%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> so do I · going to · present continuous · present simple · all A1 grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Simple Past — Regular Verbs</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">so do I · going to · present continuous · present simple · all A1 grammar</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">yesterday / last week / last month / last year / in 2020 / two years ago</div><div class="vd">past time expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">a long time ago / once / twice / many times / in those days</div><div class="vd">frequency and manner in the past</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">When…? / How long ago…? / How long did it take?</div><div class="vd">past time questions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I remember / I forgot / I learnt / I found out / I realised</div><div class="vd">memory and discovery verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">It was… / That was… / Those were…</div><div class="vd">past evaluation expressions — preview was/were</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Simple Past Regular — verb + -ed, Did — Past Questions and Negatives</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Simple Past Regular — verb + -ed</div><div class="ge">Add -ed to make the past. Spelling rules apply. Used for completed actions at a specific past time.</div><div class="ex">I walked to school yesterday. / She worked late last night.</div><div class="ex">They played tennis on Saturday. / We watched a film last weekend.</div><div class="ex">He stopped smoking last year. (double p) / She studied all day. (y to i)</div><div class="ex">I did not go — I stayed at home. (not: I did not stayed)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Did — Past Questions and Negatives</div><div class="ge">Did + base verb for ALL persons. Never did + past form — the most common simple past error.</div><div class="ex">Did you walk to work yesterday? — Yes, I did. / No, I did not.</div><div class="ex">Did she study at the weekend? — No, she did not. She played tennis.</div><div class="ex">I did not watch TV last night. / He did not work on Sunday.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Simple Past — Regular Verbs</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–20</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">so do I · going to · present continuous · present simple · all A1 grammar + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Simple Past — Regular Verbs to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#9878;&#65039; My Life With and Without · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; My Life With and Without</div><div class="st">A time in your life that changed everything.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: What did you do yesterday? Three sentences in the past tense only. Activated immediately.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Tell the story of a change in your life. When did it happen? What did you do? 'I moved to France two years ago. I did not speak French. I studied every day.'</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Did not + base verb is the most common error. Board: did not go NOT did not went.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Tell me about your life before now — where you lived, what you studied, what you did at weekends. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Simple past regular now active. Students can now describe the past — a huge leap in expressive ability.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 20 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–28</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 20 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Simple Past — Regular Verbs using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(26)">&#8592; Unit 27</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(28)">Unit 29 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-28"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 29 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Simple Past — Irregular Verbs</div><div class="unit-desc">The most common irregular verbs are learned in context. Was/were complete the past of to be. Students can now narrate real stories combining past and present — a landmark moment at A1.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:95%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> simple past regular · going to · present continuous · present simple · all A1 grammar</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Simple Past — Irregular Verbs</div><div class="lesson-sub">New vocabulary + spiral recycling</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">simple past regular · going to · present continuous · present simple · all A1 grammar</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">was / were — past of to be</div><div class="vd">I was / she was / we were / they were</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">went / came / said / got / made / took / saw / knew / gave / found</div><div class="vd">10 most essential irregulars</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">had / ate / drank / slept / woke / left / bought / thought / wrote / read</div><div class="vd">10 more key irregulars</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">How was it? / What was it like? / It was amazing / terrible / unforgettable</div><div class="vd">past experience questions and reactions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Before… / After… / When… / Suddenly… / Then… / Finally…</div><div class="vd">narrative connectors — first story-telling language</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Context First</div><div class="ad">Every new word used immediately in a sentence with prior grammar — no isolated drilling.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Spiral Integration</div><div class="ad">Write 3 sentences: new vocabulary + grammar from 3 different prior units.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Was / Were — Past of To Be, Irregular Past Forms — always learned in context</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Was / Were — Past of To Be</div><div class="ge">Parallel to am/is/are from Unit 1 but for the past. Was = I/he/she/it. Were = you/we/they.</div><div class="ex">I was at home yesterday. / She was tired last night. / It was a beautiful day.</div><div class="ex">They were in Paris last summer. / We were students together.</div><div class="ex">Was it expensive? — Yes, it was. / No, it was not.</div><div class="ex">Were you at school? — Yes, we were. / No, we were not.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Irregular Past Forms — always learned in context</div><div class="ge">Never learn a list alone — always use irregular forms in complete sentences so meaning is clear.</div><div class="ex">I went to Italy last year and I ate incredible pasta.</div><div class="ex">She came home late because she took the wrong bus.</div><div class="ex">We saw a fantastic film and then we had dinner at a restaurant.</div><div class="ex">He did not come — he felt ill so he stayed at home.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">New vs Old Grammar</div><div class="ad">10 mixed sentences. Students identify which grammar rule applies.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Error Hospital</div><div class="ad">5 new grammar errors + 3 prior unit errors. Students correct and explain.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Simple Past — Irregular Verbs</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral: all A1 grammar and vocabulary active</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — Units 1–21</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">simple past regular · going to · present continuous · present simple · all A1 grammar + all new vocabulary and grammar from this unit</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Complete Integration Task</div><div class="ad">Students must use the new grammar point AND at least 3 prior grammar points in every extended answer.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web</div><div class="ad">Connect Simple Past — Irregular Verbs to at least 5 other vocabulary areas from prior units. Speak for 2 minutes without stopping.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Long Story</div><div class="ad">Tell a continuous story weaving vocabulary from 5+ units and 5+ grammar points together.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision</div><div class="lesson-sub">&#128172; The Greatest Quotes · Full revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128172; The Greatest Quotes</div><div class="st">A moment or experience that taught you something important.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Say three things you did last week using irregular past verbs. Pressure activates irregular forms.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Tell a story about an experience that changed you. Where did you go? Who did you meet? What did you see? How did you feel?</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Was/were discrimination + past irregular errors — I goed, she taked. Board the 10 most common irregulars.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 3 min: Tell me a story about a trip or a memorable moment. Use was/were and at least 5 irregular verbs. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Irregular past + was/were now active. Full past narrative now possible. Students can tell real stories.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 21 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–29</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Identify 8 new vocabulary items from pictures or definitions</div><div class=ei>Fill 4 gap sentences using vocabulary from Unit 21 + one prior unit</div><div class=ei>Match words to definitions across this unit topic</div><div class=ei>Write 3 sentences integrating new vocabulary with prior grammar</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences using the new grammar point correctly</div><div class=ei>Multi-grammar discrimination: choose from all grammar points covered so far</div><div class=ei>Write 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 2 new grammar errors + 2 errors from earlier units</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>2-min spoken task on Simple Past — Irregular Verbs using all active grammar</div><div class=ei>Answer 4 spontaneous questions integrating this topic with prior vocabulary</div><div class=ei>Ask the examiner 3 questions using the new grammar structure</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write 8–10 sentences. Must include the new grammar (x2) + at least 3 prior grammar points + vocabulary from at least 3 topic areas.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(27)">&#8592; Unit 28</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(29)">Unit 30 &#8594;</button></div></div>
<div class="unit-block" id="unit-30"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 31 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">The Calendar — Dates, Months &amp; Ordinals</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn all 12 months, full ordinal numbers 1st–31st and how to say and write dates and years correctly. This completes the time system started in Units 2 and 15.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:86%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral:</strong> numbers (U2) · on/in (U15) · when? (U26) · seasons (U20) · going to (U22) · past simple (U28/U29)</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — The Calendar</div><div class="lesson-sub">Months · Ordinals · Dates · Years</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">numbers (U2)</span><span class="vr">seasons (U20)</span><span class="vr">at/on/in (U15)</span><span class="vr">when? (U26)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">January / February / March / April / May / June</div><div class="vd">months 1–6</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">July / August / September / October / November / December</div><div class="vd">months 7–12</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">first / second / third … tenth</div><div class="vd">ordinals 1–10</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">eleventh / twelfth / thirteenth … twentieth</div><div class="vd">ordinals 11–20</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">twenty-first … thirty-first</div><div class="vd">ordinals 21–31</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">What is the date today? / Today is the 3rd of June.</div><div class="vd">asking and giving dates</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">When is your birthday? / My birthday is on the 15th of March.</div><div class="vd">birthday expressions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">in 1990 / in the 1990s / in the 21st century</div><div class="vd">years and decades</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">leap year / public holiday / bank holiday</div><div class="vd">special calendar terms</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Month Race</div><div class="ad">Write all 12 months in order. Which have 30 days? 31? 28/29?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Birthday Line-Up</div><div class="ad">Find everyone's birthday and arrange in calendar order.</div><div class=ap>When is your birthday? — The 14th of February. — Mine is the 3rd of March, so I go after you!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Ordinals · on + date · Saying Years</div><div class="lesson-sub">1st–31st · on the 5th of March · 1990 = nineteen ninety</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Ordinal Numbers — formation</div><div class="ge">Most add -th. Exceptions: 1st/2nd/3rd. Spelling changes: five→fifth, nine→ninth, twelve→twelfth.</div><div class="ex">1st=first / 2nd=second / 3rd=third / 4th=fourth</div><div class="ex">5th=fifth / 8th=eighth / 9th=ninth / 12th=twelfth</div><div class="ex">20th=twentieth / 21st=twenty-first / 31st=thirty-first</div><div class="ex">The 4th of July is American Independence Day.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Dates — spoken vs written</div><div class="ge">Written: 3rd March. Spoken: always "the third of March" with the.</div><div class="ex">Written: 25 December / 25th December</div><div class="ex">Spoken: the twenty-fifth of December</div><div class="ex">When is Christmas? — On the twenty-fifth of December.</div><div class="ex">My birthday is on the first of May. When is yours?</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Saying Years</div><div class="ge">Up to 1999: two parts. 2000+: full number or two parts.</div><div class="ex">1990=nineteen ninety / 1845=eighteen forty-five</div><div class="ex">2000=two thousand / 2005=two thousand and five</div><div class="ex">2024=twenty twenty-four OR two thousand and twenty-four</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Date Dictation</div><div class="ad">Teacher says dates, students write. Then students say dates aloud.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Famous Birthdays</div><div class="ad">Say famous people's birthdays using ordinals + months + years.</div><div class=ap>Shakespeare: twenty-third of April, fifteen sixty-four.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Dates in Real Life</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · ordinals · months · on/in · going to · past simple</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">months 1–12</span><span class="vr">ordinals 1–31</span><span class="vr">on + date (U15)</span><span class="vr">in + year (U15)</span><span class="vr">when? (U26)</span><span class="vr">going to (U22)</span><span class="vr">past simple (U28/U29)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Year in Review</div><div class="ad">Important dates using ordinals + months + years.</div><div class=ap>I was born on the fifteenth of June, nineteen eighty-eight. I started my first job on the third of March, two thousand and ten.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Calendar Quiz</div><div class="ad">Calendar trivia using ordinals. Points for correct date format.</div><div class=ap>When is New Year's Day? — The first of January.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Plan the Year</div><div class="ad">5 future plans each with a specific date using going to + ordinals.</div><div class=ap>On the fourteenth of February I am going to have dinner with my partner.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Let's Celebrate</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: The most important date in your year</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#127881; LET'S CELEBRATE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">What is the most important date in your calendar — and why?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Say today's date in full — day, ordinal, month, year. Then everyone says their birthday. Ordinals + months activated immediately.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: What is your most important date? A birthday? Anniversary? National holiday? "The twenty-fifth of December is very important. On that day we always have a big dinner. My grandmother was born on Christmas Day — the twenty-fifth of December, nineteen thirty-eight!"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Ordinal errors (twenty-oneth), spoken year errors, on vs in with dates.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Tell me about your year — the important dates, what happens, what you plan to do. Use ordinals and months for every date. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Ordinals + months + on/in dates all active. Calendar language now complete.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 31</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–31</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write all 12 months from memory</div><div class=ei>Write ordinals for: 1/3/5/8/9/12/20/21/31</div><div class=ei>Write these dates in words: 14/02 / 25/12 / 01/01</div><div class=ei>Say these years in words: 1990 / 2005 / 2024 / 1845</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write 5 dates in full spoken form: "the ___ of ___"</div><div class=ei>Choose on or in for 8 date expressions</div><div class=ei>Answer: When is your birthday? When were you born? What year did you start school?</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 date/ordinal errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Say 5 important dates in your life — full ordinal + month + year</div><div class=ei>Describe what happens on 3 dates using present simple + going to</div><div class=ei>Answer: When is your birthday? What will you do? — 2 min</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write about important dates in your year (8–10 sentences). Every date in full words. Must include: ordinals (×5) · months (×4) · on + date (×3) · in + year (×2) · going to for a future date.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(28)">&#8592; Unit 29</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(30)">Unit 31 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-31"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 32 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Special Occasions &amp; Invitations</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn to invite, accept and decline for all major celebrations. Would you like to as a formal invitation and I'm afraid as a polite softener are formally taught. Occasion vocabulary covers personal and world celebrations.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:88%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral:</strong> Would you like (U9) · Let's/Shall we (U22) · going to (U22) · on + date (U31) · ordinals (U31) · can/can't (U7)</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Special Occasions &amp; Invitations</div><div class="lesson-sub">Celebrations · Occasion greetings · Inviting · Accepting · Declining</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">Would you like (U9)</span><span class="vr">Let's/Shall we (U22)</span><span class="vr">going to (U22)</span><span class="vr">on + date (U31)</span><span class="vr">months+ordinals (U31)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">birthday / anniversary / wedding / graduation / retirement</div><div class="vd">personal occasions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Christmas / New Year / Easter / Eid / Diwali / Hanukkah</div><div class="vd">world celebrations</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">party / dinner / celebration / ceremony / reception</div><div class="vd">event types</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Happy Birthday! / Congratulations! / Happy New Year! / Merry Christmas!</div><div class="vd">occasion greetings</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Would you like to come to…? / Are you free on…? / Can you make it?</div><div class="vd">inviting</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I'd love to! / That sounds great! / I'll be there!</div><div class="vd">accepting</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">I'm afraid I can't. / I'm sorry, I have other plans.</div><div class="vd">declining politely</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">gift / present / card / flowers / cake / candles / decorations</div><div class="vd">celebration objects</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">celebrate / invite / organise / attend / toast / sing / dance</div><div class="vd">celebration verbs</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Occasion Match</div><div class="ad">Match occasions to correct greetings.</div><div class=ap>Birthday→Happy Birthday! / Wedding→Congratulations! / New Year→Happy New Year!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Write an Invitation</div><div class="ad">Write a short party invitation. Others accept or decline politely.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Would You Like to · I'm afraid · Polite Social Language</div><div class="lesson-sub">Invitations · Polite declining · Occasion questions</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Would You Like to + infinitive — invitation</div><div class="ge">More polite than Do you want to. Used for all social invitations.</div><div class="ex">Would you like to come to my birthday party on Saturday?</div><div class="ex">Would you like to have dinner with us on the 14th?</div><div class="ex">I'd love to! (= Yes, I would) / I'm afraid I can't. (polite no)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">I'm afraid + negative — polite declining</div><div class="ge">I'm afraid softens bad news. Essential for social situations at A1.</div><div class="ex">I'm afraid I can't come — I have other plans.</div><div class="ex">I'm afraid she is not available on that day.</div><div class="ex">Maybe next time? / Can we arrange another day?</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">What + to be — occasion questions</div><div class="ge">Asking about purpose and details of events.</div><div class="ex">What is the party for? — It is for my sister's birthday.</div><div class="ex">What is the celebration? — It is our 10th wedding anniversary!</div><div class="ex">What time is the dinner? — At 8 on Saturday the 15th.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Accept or Decline?</div><div class="ad">Receive invitations — respond appropriately. Some accept, some decline. All responses polite and complete.</div><div class=ap>You are invited to a party on Friday but you have a work dinner. → Thank you so much! I'm afraid I can't come — I have a work dinner. Maybe next time?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Plan a Party</div><div class="ad">Plan a party: date, time, venue. Then invite each other using Would you like to.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Invitations and Social Situations</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · would you like to · I'm afraid · occasion vocabulary · dates</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">would you like to</span><span class="vr">I'm afraid</span><span class="vr">Let's/Shall we (U22)</span><span class="vr">going to (U22)</span><span class="vr">on + date (U31)</span><span class="vr">ordinals+months (U31)</span><span class="vr">celebration vocabulary</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Party Role-Play</div><div class="ad">A organises a party, invites B. B asks questions (when? where? what for?) and accepts or declines with a reason.</div><div class=ap>Would you like to come to my graduation party? It is on the twenty-third of June. — I'd love to! What time? — At 8. Shall I bring something? — Just yourself!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Occasion Speech</div><div class="ad">Pick a celebration card, speak for 90 seconds using all vocabulary.</div><div class=ap>It is my friend's birthday on the fifth of March. I am going to organise a surprise party. Would you like to come? I'm afraid you cannot tell her!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">World Celebrations</div><div class="ad">Present a celebration from your culture using dates + vocabulary.</div><div class=ap>In Greece we celebrate Easter in April or May. On that day families have a big dinner. This year Easter is on the twentieth of April.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Let's Celebrate</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: The celebration that means most to you</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#127881; LET'S CELEBRATE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">The celebration that means most to you — describe it completely.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Invite the person next to you to a celebration using Would you like to. They accept or decline politely.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: What is your favourite celebration? When? What do you do? Who comes? "My favourite is New Year. We always have a big family dinner on the thirty-first of December. At midnight we toast. I'd like to invite all of you!"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Would you like to (not would you like that) and I'm afraid correctly. Ordinal + month combinations.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Describe your favourite celebration completely — when, who, what, where, why. Then invite everyone. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Would you like to + I'm afraid + occasion vocabulary + ordinals + months all active.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 32</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–32</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Match 8 occasions to correct greetings</div><div class=ei>Fill: Would you like to ___ / I'm afraid I ___ / That sounds ___</div><div class=ei>Write 5 celebration objects from pictures</div><div class=ei>Write accept or decline for 4 situations with full response</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write 3 invitations using Would you like to + full date</div><div class=ei>Write 3 polite declinations using I'm afraid</div><div class=ei>Complete 4 occasion questions using What + to be</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 invitation/declining errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Invite the examiner to an event — full details — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Decline two invitations politely with reasons</div><div class=ei>Describe your favourite celebration — 2 min</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a party invitation AND a polite reply declining it (8–10 sentences). Invitation: Would you like to · full date · time · place · occasion · what will happen. Decline: I'm afraid · reason · alternative.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(29)">&#8592; Unit 30</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(31)">Unit 32 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-32"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 33 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Quantities, too/enough &amp; one/ones</div><div class="unit-desc">The complete A1 quantity system: a lot of / a few / a little / too much / too many / not enough. Too + adjective and not + adjective + enough are formally introduced. one/ones substitution and Whose complete the grammar.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:91%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral:</strong> some/any (U6) · countable/uncountable (U6) · how much/how many (U6/U26) · adjectives (U4) · possessives (U3)</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Quantity Expressions</div><div class="lesson-sub">a lot of · a few · a little · too much/many · not enough · one/ones · Whose</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">some/any (U6)</span><span class="vr">how much/how many (U6/U26)</span><span class="vr">countable/uncountable (U6)</span><span class="vr">adjectives (U4)</span><span class="vr">possessives (U3)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">a lot of / lots of</div><div class="vd">large quantity — countable and uncountable</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">a few</div><div class="vd">small number — countable: a few apples</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">a little</div><div class="vd">small amount — uncountable: a little milk</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">too much</div><div class="vd">more than needed — uncountable: too much sugar</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">too many</div><div class="vd">more than needed — countable: too many people</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">not enough</div><div class="vd">less than needed: not enough time / chairs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">too + adjective</div><div class="vd">more than acceptable: too expensive / too far</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">not + adjective + enough</div><div class="vd">less than needed: not big enough / not fast enough</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">enough + noun</div><div class="vd">sufficient: enough money / enough space</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">one / ones</div><div class="vd">substitution: the red one / the big ones</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Whose + noun? / Whose is this?</div><div class="vd">possessive question word</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Too Much or Not Enough?</div><div class="ad">Describe problems using too much/many or not enough.</div><div class=ap>Too many cars. Too much noise. Not enough parks. Not enough green space.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Which One?</div><div class="ad">Teacher points to objects. Students respond using one/ones with adjective.</div><div class=ap>Which bag? — The red one. / Whose jacket is this? — It's mine.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Too/Enough · a few/a little · one/ones · Whose</div><div class="lesson-sub">Complete quantity and substitution system</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Too + adjective / Not + adjective + enough</div><div class="ge">Too = more than acceptable. Not enough = less than needed.</div><div class="ex">This coffee is too hot. I cannot drink it.</div><div class="ex">She is too tired to go out. (too + adjective + to + infinitive)</div><div class="ex">The flat is not big enough for our family.</div><div class="ex">I am not tall enough to reach the shelf!</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">a few / a little — small quantities</div><div class="ge">a few = small number (countable). a little = small amount (uncountable).</div><div class="ex">I have got a few friends in Paris — about 3 or 4.</div><div class="ex">Can I have a little milk in my coffee, please?</div><div class="ex">I speak a little French. / She has got a few minutes to talk.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">one / ones — substitution pronouns</div><div class="ge">Replace a noun already mentioned. one = singular, ones = plural.</div><div class="ex">I like this jacket. — Which one? — The blue one.</div><div class="ex">Do you prefer these shoes? — No, the black ones.</div><div class="ex">Have you got a smaller one? / I'd like the ones in the window.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Whose — possessive question word</div><div class="ge">Asks who something belongs to.</div><div class="ex">Whose bag is this? — It's Maria's. / It's mine.</div><div class="ex">Whose are these keys? — They're his.</div><div class="ex">Whose phone is ringing? — It's not mine!</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Sentence Transformation</div><div class="ad">Transform using too/enough.</div><div class=ap>The soup is very hot → The soup is too hot to eat. / The room is very small → Not big enough.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">One/Ones Quick Drill</div><div class="ad">Teacher says noun + adjective. Students say one or ones immediately.</div><div class=ap>The red shirt → The red one? / The big shoes → The big ones!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Quantities in Real Situations</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · too/enough · a few/a little · one/ones · whose</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">too + adjective</span><span class="vr">not + adjective + enough</span><span class="vr">a few/a little</span><span class="vr">a lot of</span><span class="vr">one/ones</span><span class="vr">Whose</span><span class="vr">some/any (U6)</span><span class="vr">how much/how many</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Perfect City</div><div class="ad">Describe ideal city using quantity language throughout.</div><div class=ap>My perfect city has a lot of parks and not too many cars. There are a few great restaurants near my house — the small one on the corner is my favourite.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Shopping Complaints</div><div class="ad">Customer is unhappy. Use too/not enough/a few/a little to complain. Ask for a different one.</div><div class=ap>This coffee is too cold and not sweet enough. Can I have a different one? — Which one? — That one, the small one.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Whose is it?</div><div class="ad">Objects collected. Ask and answer using Whose + one/ones + possessives.</div><div class=ap>Whose bag is this? — It might be Marco's — he has got a black one.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Debatable &amp; Relatable</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Do we have too much stuff and not enough time?</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128293; DEBATABLE &amp; RELATABLE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Do we have too much stuff and not enough time? The modern problem of excess.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Name 3 things you have too much of and 3 you do not have enough of. Activated in 60 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you have too many things? Too much on your plate? "I have too many clothes but always say I have not got enough. I spend too much money on food — I go to restaurants a few times a week. But I do not have enough time to cook!"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: a few vs a little (countable/uncountable), too much vs too many, one/ones substitution.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: Your life in quantity language — a lot of / too much / not enough / a little more. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Full quantity system active: too/enough + a few/a little + one/ones + Whose. Precision of all prior vocabulary transformed.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 33</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–33</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Choose: a few/a little/a lot of/too much/too many/not enough for 8 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write one or ones for 6 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write Whose questions for 4 answers</div><div class=ei>Fill: too + adjective OR not + adjective + enough for 6 situations</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Transform 4 sentences: very → too</div><div class=ei>Transform 4 using not enough</div><div class=ei>Replace nouns with one/ones in 5 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write Whose questions and answers for 4 situations</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe home/city using too/not enough/a lot of — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Shopping roleplay: complain using too/not enough, ask for different ones — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Answer: Whose is this? (5 objects) using possessives and one/ones</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write about what you have too much of and not enough of (8–10 sentences). Must include: too + adjective (×2) · not + adjective + enough (×2) · a few/a little (×1 each) · a lot of · one/ones (×2) · Whose (×1).</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(30)">&#8592; Unit 31</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(32)">Unit 33 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-33"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 34 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Cooking &amp; Recipes</div><div class="unit-desc">Students learn cooking verbs, kitchen equipment, measurements and recipe language. Imperatives are applied in a vivid practical context. Recipe sequence language consolidates connectors from Unit 16. Quantity expressions from Unit 33 are woven throughout.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:94%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral:</strong> food vocabulary (U6) · a little/a few/a lot of (U33) · imperatives (U13) · first/then/finally (U16) · for + time (U15)</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Cooking &amp; Recipes</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cooking verbs · Kitchen equipment · Recipe language · Measurements</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">food vocabulary (U6)</span><span class="vr">countable/uncountable (U6)</span><span class="vr">a little/a few/a lot of (U33)</span><span class="vr">imperatives (U13)</span><span class="vr">there is/there are (U4)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">boil / fry / bake / roast / grill / steam / stir / mix</div><div class="vd">cooking verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">chop / slice / peel / grate / pour / add / heat / cool</div><div class="vd">preparation verbs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">oven / pan / pot / knife / chopping board / bowl / spoon</div><div class="vd">kitchen equipment</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">ingredient / recipe / dish / meal / portion / serving</div><div class="vd">recipe vocabulary</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">a teaspoon of / a tablespoon of / a cup of / a gram of / a litre of</div><div class="vd">measurements</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">raw / cooked / boiled / fried / baked / grilled / crispy / tender</div><div class="vd">food texture/state</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">medium heat / high heat / for 20 minutes / until golden</div><div class="vd">cooking instructions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Kitchen Vocab Race</div><div class="ad">Label kitchen equipment from a picture. Then mime a cooking action — others guess the verb.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Signature Dish</div><div class="ad">Describe a dish using: ingredients (a little/a few/some) + cooking verbs.</div><div class=ap>To make pasta carbonara you need some pasta, a few eggs, a little cream and a lot of Parmesan. First boil the pasta. Then fry the bacon.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Imperatives for Recipes · for + time · First/Then/Finally</div><div class="lesson-sub">Boil the water. / Cook for 20 minutes until golden. / Sequence connectors.</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Imperatives for Cooking Instructions</div><div class="ge">Recipes use imperative throughout. Extends classroom imperatives (U13) to a new practical context.</div><div class="ex">Boil the water for 10 minutes.</div><div class="ex">Add a little salt. Do not add too much.</div><div class="ex">Chop the onions and fry them in a little oil.</div><div class="ex">Bake at 180 degrees for 25 minutes until golden.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">For + time / Until + description</div><div class="ge">Cook for + time tells how long. Until + description tells when to stop.</div><div class="ex">Boil the pasta for 10 minutes.</div><div class="ex">Fry the onions for 5 minutes until they are soft.</div><div class="ex">Bake for 30 minutes until golden and crispy.</div><div class="ex">Leave to cool for at least 20 minutes before serving.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">First / Then / Next / After that / Finally in recipes</div><div class="ge">Sequence connectors (U16) in a practical, memorable context.</div><div class="ex">First, heat the oil in a pan.</div><div class="ex">Then add the onions and cook for 5 minutes.</div><div class="ex">Next, add the tomatoes and a little salt.</div><div class="ex">Finally, serve with fresh bread and a glass of wine!</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Recipe Dictation</div><div class="ad">Teacher dictates a simple recipe. Students write in order using imperatives + sequence words.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Fix the Recipe</div><div class="ad">A recipe with deliberate errors — wrong connector order, wrong imperative, too much/too many confusion.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Share a Recipe</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · cooking vocabulary · imperatives · for + time · first/then/finally · quantities</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">cooking verbs + equipment</span><span class="vr">imperatives (U13)</span><span class="vr">first/then/finally (U16)</span><span class="vr">a little/a few/a lot of (U33)</span><span class="vr">for + time (U15)</span><span class="vr">food vocabulary (U6)</span><span class="vr">countable/uncountable (U6)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Cook It Live</div><div class="ad">Explain how to make a dish step by step. Class asks: how much? how many? how long?</div><div class=ap>First boil some water. Add a lot of salt — this is important! Then add 100g of pasta. Cook for 10 minutes. While the pasta cooks, fry a few cloves of garlic in a little olive oil. — How much oil? — Just a tablespoon. Add tomatoes and cook 5 more minutes. Drain and mix. Serve immediately!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Recipe Swap</div><div class="ad">Describe a recipe from your culture. Partner asks: How much? How many? How long?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Worst Cook</div><div class="ad">Describe a kitchen disaster using too much/not enough + sequence.</div><div class=ap>I tried to bake a cake. First I added too much flour. Then not enough sugar. I cooked it for too long. Finally I took it out — too hard and not sweet enough. A total disaster!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Let's Celebrate</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: A dish that tells a story</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#127881; LET'S CELEBRATE — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">A dish that tells a story — food that connects you to a person, a place or a memory.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Name one dish you know how to make. Give the first instruction using an imperative.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Is there a dish that connects you to family or your country? "My grandmother always made a special soup. First she chopped a lot of vegetables. Then she boiled them for at least two hours. She always added a little secret ingredient. I never found out what it was!"</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: Check imperative use, for + time, and a little vs a few vs a lot of.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 2 min: A dish important to you — who makes it, how, what it tastes like, when you eat it. Cooking verbs, imperatives and sequence words throughout. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Cooking vocabulary + imperatives + sequence + quantities all active. Food topic now fully expressible.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 34</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–34</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Label 8 kitchen items from pictures</div><div class=ei>Match 8 cooking verbs to definitions</div><div class=ei>Write measurement expression for 5 recipe ingredients</div><div class=ei>Describe texture/state of 4 foods: raw/cooked/crispy/tender</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write 5 imperative instructions for a recipe</div><div class=ei>Complete: Cook ___ 15 minutes / Fry ___ golden / Bake ___ 200 degrees</div><div class=ei>Reorder a jumbled 6-step recipe using first/then/next/after that/finally</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 recipe sentences — wrong imperative/connector/quantity</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Explain how to make a simple dish step by step — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Answer How much/How many/How long for 5 recipe questions</div><div class=ei>Describe a cooking disaster using too/not enough — 90 sec</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a complete recipe (8–12 sentences). Must use: imperatives throughout · first/then/next/after that/finally · a little/a few/a lot of (×1 each) · for + time (×2) · until + description · food vocabulary from U6.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(31)">&#8592; Unit 32</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(33)">Unit 34 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-34"><div class="unit-header"><div class="unit-num">Unit 35 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div><span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span><div class="unit-title">Public Signs, Services &amp; Verb + Infinitive</div><div class="unit-desc">Students read and respond to public signs and navigate services. Have to / do not have to and need to complete the A1 obligation system. The full verb + to + infinitive pattern (want/need/plan/hope/try/learn/would like) is formally consolidated.</div><div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:97%"></div></div></div><div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral:</strong> should/shouldn't (U20) · can/can't (U7) · would like to (U9/U32) · going to (U22) · imperatives (U13) · all prior modals</span></div><div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Public Signs, Services &amp; Notices</div><div class="lesson-sub">Signs · Public services · have to / need to · verb + infinitive expressions</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">can/can't (U7)</span><span class="vr">imperatives (U13)</span><span class="vr">places in town (U7)</span><span class="vr">should/shouldn't (U20)</span><span class="vr">question words (U26)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Exit / Entrance / Push / Pull / Open / Closed</div><div class="vd">door signs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">No smoking / No entry / No parking / Keep out</div><div class="vd">prohibition signs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Emergency exit / Fire escape / First aid / Call 999 or 112</div><div class="vd">emergency signs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Out of order / Under construction / Wet floor / Caution</div><div class="vd">warning signs</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Queue here / Wait here / Take a number / Pay here</div><div class="vd">service instructions</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">information desk / customer service / lost property / reception</div><div class="vd">public service points</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">have to / has to / do not have to</div><div class="vd">obligation and no obligation</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">need to / do not need to</div><div class="vd">necessity and no necessity</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">want to / plan to / hope to / try to / learn to</div><div class="vd">verb + infinitive expressions</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Signs Around Us</div><div class="ad">Look at 12 public signs. Explain each using: You must / You cannot / You should / It means…</div><div class=ap>This sign means you cannot smoke here. / This means you have to queue. / Out of order — you need to use the other entrance.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">I Need / I Have to</div><div class="ad">Describe situations using need to and have to.</div><div class=ap>My phone is dead — I need to find a charger. / The sign says No Entry — we have to go another way.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — Have to / Need to · Verb + to + Infinitive Full System</div><div class="lesson-sub">Obligation · Necessity · want/need/plan/hope/try/learn + infinitive</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Have to / Has to — obligation</div><div class="ge">Have to = external rule or necessity. Different from should (advice). Do not have to = no obligation.</div><div class="ex">I have to go to work at 9 — it is the rule.</div><div class="ex">She has to wear a uniform. / We have to show our passport.</div><div class="ex">Do you have to work on Saturdays? — No, I do not have to.</div><div class="ex">You do not have to come — it is not necessary.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Need to — personal necessity</div><div class="ge">Need to = I feel it is necessary. Often interchangeable with have to informally.</div><div class="ex">I need to call my mother tonight.</div><div class="ex">She needs to buy a new phone — hers is broken.</div><div class="ex">Do I need to book in advance? — Yes, you do.</div><div class="ex">You do not need to pay now — you can pay later.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Verb + to + Infinitive — the full A1 system</div><div class="ge">Many A1 verbs are followed by to + infinitive. Students must recognise and use this pattern confidently.</div><div class="ex">want to → I want to learn French.</div><div class="ex">need to → She needs to study more.</div><div class="ex">have to → We have to leave now.</div><div class="ex">plan to → I plan to visit Italy next summer.</div><div class="ex">hope to → He hopes to find a better job.</div><div class="ex">try to → She tries to speak English every day.</div><div class="ex">would like to → I'd like to come to your party.</div><div class="ex">learn to → He is learning to drive.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Should vs Have to vs Need to</div><div class="ad">Choose the correct modal for 12 situations.</div><div class=ap>You are ill → You should see a doctor. / Sign says No Entry → You have to go another way. / My English is weak → I need to practise more.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Verb + Infinitive Chains</div><div class="ad">Each student adds a sentence using a different verb + infinitive.</div><div class=ap>I want to travel. → I need to save money. → I plan to work extra. → I hope to go to Japan. → I try to spend less.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Real World Situations</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full spiral · have to/need to · verb + infinitive · public signs · should · can</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">have to/need to</span><span class="vr">should/shouldn't (U20)</span><span class="vr">can/can't (U7)</span><span class="vr">want/plan/hope/try + to</span><span class="vr">going to (U22)</span><span class="vr">imperatives (U13)</span><span class="vr">public signs vocabulary</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Public Situation Role-Play</div><div class="ad">A encounters a sign or situation. B explains what it means and what to do.</div><div class=ap>The sign says Queue Here. → You have to wait. You cannot go straight to the desk. — How long do I need to wait? — Take a number. You also have to fill in this form first.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Plans and Hopes</div><div class="ad">Use the full verb + infinitive system to describe the future.</div><div class=ap>I want to improve my English. I need to practise speaking every day. I plan to take an exam next year. I hope to get a good score. I try to watch one English film every week. I would like to visit London and I have to save money for it.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Rules of Life</div><div class="ad">Describe rules in your life using have to + do not have to.</div><div class=ap>At work I have to arrive before 9. I have to wear a suit on Mondays. I do not have to work at weekends but I sometimes choose to. I need to check my email every hour.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With &amp; Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Life with and without rules — freedom vs structure</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Life with and without rules — do we need structure to be free?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span>Warm-up: Name 3 things you have to do every day and 3 you do not have to do. have to/do not have to in 60 seconds.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span>Main conversation: Do you have many rules in your life? At work? At home? "I have to go to work at 9. I do not have to wear a uniform but I need to dress professionally. I want to change my job because I hope to work from home. I plan to find something new next year."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span>Language in action: have to vs need to vs should vs must — the full A1 modal spectrum. Board the differences clearly.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span>Fluency challenge 3 min: Your life — what you have to do, want to do, hope to do, need to do, plan to do. Full verb + infinitive system. Do not stop.</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Have to/need to + full verb+infinitive system now active. A1 modal verb spectrum complete.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 35</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–35</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write what 8 public signs mean using You have to / You cannot / It means…</div><div class=ei>Match 6 verb + infinitive collocations: want/need/plan/hope/try/learn + to</div><div class=ei>Fill: have to / has to / do not have to / need to / do not need to for 6 situations</div><div class=ei>Write the correct public service for 4 situations</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Choose: should/have to/need to/can for 8 situations</div><div class=ei>Write 4 sentences using different verb + infinitive combinations</div><div class=ei>Transform: "It is necessary for me to go." → "I have to go." (4 sentences)</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 4 have to/need to/verb+infinitive errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe 5 rules in your life using have to/do not have to — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Describe your plans and hopes using 5 different verb + infinitive structures — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Explain what 5 public signs mean using can/have to/should</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write about your life rules and future plans (8–10 sentences). Must include: have to (×2) · do not have to (×1) · need to (×2) · want to · plan to · hope to · try to (×1 each) · should · can. Every modal correct in context.</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="nav-buttons"><button class="nav-btn" onclick="showUnit(32)">&#8592; Unit 33</button><button class="nav-btn primary" onclick="showUnit(34)">Unit 35 &#8594;</button></div></div><div class="unit-block" id="unit-36">
<div class="unit-header">
<div class="unit-num">Unit 36 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div>
<span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span>
<div class="unit-title">The Definite Article, Possessive Pronouns &amp; Could</div>
<div class="unit-desc">The three remaining CEFR A1 grammar points are formally taught: <em>the</em> (definite article — the most common word in English), possessive pronouns <em>mine/yours/his/hers/ours/theirs</em>, and <em>could</em> for polite requests. Irregular plurals and furniture vocabulary are fully consolidated. This is the last grammar unit before the A1 final exam.</div>
<div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:99%"></div></div>
</div>
<div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> a/an (U2) · possessive adjectives my/your/his/her (U3) · can (U7) · plural nouns (U2) · rooms + furniture (U4) · there is/are (U4) · superlatives always use <em>the</em> (U25) · Whose (U33) · ALL prior grammar and vocabulary</span></div>
<div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Furniture, Irregular Plurals &amp; Consolidation</div><div class="lesson-sub">Furniture in full · Irregular plurals consolidated · Possessive pronouns · Could</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">rooms (U4) — furniture extends this</span><span class="vr">have got (U3) — describing furniture</span><span class="vr">a/an (U2) — now completed by the</span><span class="vr">there is/there are (U4)</span><span class="vr">possessive adjectives (U3) — now completed by possessive pronouns</span><span class="vr">can (U7) — now joined by could</span><span class="vr">plural nouns (U2) — irregular forms consolidated</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New & Consolidated Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">sofa / armchair / coffee table / bookshelf / wardrobe</div><div class="vd">living room furniture</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bed / bedside table / wardrobe / chest of drawers / mirror</div><div class="vd">bedroom furniture</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">fridge / freezer / washing machine / dishwasher / microwave</div><div class="vd">kitchen appliances</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">desk / lamp / curtains / carpet / rug / painting / cushion</div><div class="vd">general home items</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">man → men / woman → women / child → children</div><div class="vd">irregular plurals — people</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">foot → feet / tooth → teeth / mouse → mice / fish → fish</div><div class="vd">irregular plurals — body/animals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">person → people / leaf → leaves / knife → knives / life → lives</div><div class="vd">more irregular plurals</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">mine / yours / his / hers / ours / theirs</div><div class="vd">possessive pronouns — full set</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">Could you…? / Could I…? / Could we…?</div><div class="vd">could for polite requests</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">the + specific noun / the + superlative / the + unique thing</div><div class="vd">definite article key uses</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Furniture Tour</div><div class="ad">Students describe their home in full using ALL furniture vocabulary — new and from U4. Must use there is/there are + have got + adjectives + the.</div><div class=ap>In my living room there is a big sofa and two armchairs. The sofa is grey and very comfortable. There is a bookshelf next to the window. The books on it are all in Italian.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Plural Rapid Fire</div><div class="ad">Teacher says a singular noun. Students say the plural immediately — regular or irregular. Mix both types.</div><div class=ap>man → men / child → children / tooth → teeth / table → tables / foot → feet / leaf → leaves / dish → dishes / mouse → mice</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — The Definite Article · Possessive Pronouns · Could · Irregular Plurals</div><div class="lesson-sub">a/an/the system complete · mine/yours/his/hers · Could you? · men/women/children/feet/teeth</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">a/an (U2)</span><span class="vr">possessive adjectives my/your/his (U3)</span><span class="vr">can (U7)</span><span class="vr">plural nouns (U2)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">The Definite Article — the</div><div class="ge">Use THE when both speaker and listener know which specific thing is meant. Four main rules at A1:</div><div class="ex">RULE 1 — Already mentioned: I have a dog. The dog is very friendly. (first mention = a, second = the)</div><div class="ex">RULE 2 — Only one exists: the sun / the moon / the internet / the world</div><div class="ex">RULE 3 — Specified/identified: the book on the table / the woman in the red coat</div><div class="ex">RULE 4 — Superlatives always use the: the best / the most expensive / the biggest</div><div class="ex">NO article: general statements — I like music. / Dogs are friendly. / Life is short.</div><div class="ex">NO article: most proper nouns — in France / at school / at home / by bus</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">A vs An vs The vs Nothing — comparison</div><div class="ge">The most important article decision at A1: which one fits?</div><div class="ex">I want a coffee. (any coffee — first mention, not specific)</div><div class="ex">The coffee is cold! (THIS coffee — already ordered, specific)</div><div class="ex">I love coffee. (coffee in general — no article)</div><div class="ex">She is the best teacher I have ever had. (superlative → the)</div><div class="ex">She is a teacher. (one of many — profession, no the)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Possessive Pronouns — mine/yours/his/hers/ours/theirs</div><div class="ge">Replace a possessive adjective + noun to avoid repetition. Different from possessive adjectives which come BEFORE a noun.</div><div class="ex">This is my bag. → This bag is mine. (possessive adjective → possessive pronoun)</div><div class="ex">Is this your jacket? — Yes, it's mine. / No, it's not mine — it's hers.</div><div class="ex">Whose keys are these? — They're his. / They might be theirs.</div><div class="ex">my → mine / your → yours / his → his / her → hers / our → ours / their → theirs</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Could — polite requests and possibility</div><div class="ge">Could is more polite and tentative than can. At A1 it is used mainly for polite requests.</div><div class="ex">Could you help me, please? (more polite than: Can you help me?)</div><div class="ex">Could I have the bill, please? / Could we sit here?</div><div class="ex">Could you speak more slowly? / Could you repeat that?</div><div class="ex">Could also expresses past ability: When I was young I could swim very fast.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Irregular Plurals — consolidated</div><div class="ge">These must be memorised — there is no rule. Drill them in sentences, never as a list alone.</div><div class="ex">man → men: There are three men at the door.</div><div class="ex">woman → women: The women in my family are all very strong.</div><div class="ex">child → children: The children are playing in the garden.</div><div class="ex">foot → feet: My feet are cold! / tooth → teeth: Brush your teeth!</div><div class="ex">mouse → mice / fish → fish / person → people / leaf → leaves / knife → knives</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">A / The / Nothing — 20 sentences</div><div class="ad">Students choose the correct article for 20 sentences covering all four rules. Includes superlatives (recycled from U25), specific/general contrast, and unique nouns.</div><div class=ap>"___ sun is very hot today." → The / "___ coffee is my favourite drink." → Nothing (general) / "___ coffee you made is perfect." → The (specific) / "She is ___ best student in the class." → the</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Mine or My? Swap Drill</div><div class="ad">Teacher says a sentence with a possessive adjective. Students restate using a possessive pronoun.</div><div class=ap>"This is my phone." → "This phone is mine." / "Is that her bag?" → "Is that bag hers?" / "These are our seats." → "These seats are ours."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Can or Could?</div><div class="ad">10 situations. Students choose can (ability/neutral request) or could (polite request).</div><div class=ap>Asking a friend for a pen casually → Can you give me a pen? / Asking a waiter in a restaurant → Could I have the menu, please?</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Complete Grammar in Natural Conversation</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full A1 spiral · the/a/an/∅ · mine/yours · could · irregular plurals · all prior grammar</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — All 36 Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">the / a / an / ∅ article system</span><span class="vr">mine/yours/his/hers/ours/theirs</span><span class="vr">could for polite requests</span><span class="vr">irregular plurals consolidated</span><span class="vr">ALL prior grammar: to be · have got · present simple · present continuous</span><span class="vr">past simple · going to · can · should · have to · need to</span><span class="vr">would like · let's · comparatives · superlatives · connectors</span><span class="vr">ALL vocabulary domains from U1–U35</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Article Challenge</div><div class="ad">Students describe their home, neighbourhood or a place they love. The rule: every single noun must have the correct article (a / an / the / nothing). Partner listens and challenges any wrong article immediately.</div><div class=ap>"I live in a flat in the centre of the city. The flat is on the third floor. There is a beautiful view of the river. The river is called the Thames. In the morning I have coffee on the balcony — a balcony is my favourite part of the flat. The coffee I drink is always Italian."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Whose is it? — Full System</div><div class="ad">Objects from students are collected. Students ask and answer using Whose + possessive adjective + possessive pronoun + could.</div><div class=ap>"Whose phone is this?" — "It might be mine! Could I have a look?" — "Yes, of course." — "Oh, it's not mine — mine is blue. Is it yours, Marco?" — "No, mine is in my bag. Maybe it's hers?" — "Yes! It's hers — it's Sara's."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Polite Café</div><div class="ad">Students role-play in a café using could throughout — ordering, asking for help, making requests. Must also use the correctly when referring to specific items.</div><div class=ap>"Could I have a table for two, please?" — "Of course. Could you follow me?" — "Could we sit by the window?" — "Certainly. Could I take your order?" — "Yes, could I have the pasta, please — the one with tomato sauce." — "And could I have the fish? Is the fish fresh today?"</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — Greatest Quotes</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: A sentence that changed how you see the world · Full A1 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#128172; THE GREATEST QUOTES — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">A sentence that changed how you see the world — in any language.</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Say a quote you love — in any language. Then say it in English if you can." The act of translation forces students to use the article system immediately and naturally.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> "What is the most important sentence you have ever heard? Who said it? Why did it change you?" Students use THE for the specific quote, the specific person, the specific moment. "The most important thing my mother ever told me was: 'The world is yours if you are kind.' I remember the day she said it. I was a child — about eight years old. The words stayed with me."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher collects article errors from student speech — this is the richest source of the/a/∅ errors in natural production. Boards corrections. Also notes could vs can errors and possessive pronoun confusion.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 3 min — PRE-FINAL CHALLENGE:</strong> "Tell me about your life, your family, your home, your work, your past and your future plans. Use everything you know. Pay attention to your articles. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; THE article system + possessive pronouns + could + irregular plurals all active in natural speech. Final grammar audit before the A1 exam.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 36 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–36 · Pre-final grammar check</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Write the irregular plural for: man / woman / child / foot / tooth / mouse / person / leaf / knife / fish</div><div class=ei>Label 10 furniture items from a room picture</div><div class=ei>Write possessive pronouns: my → ___ / your → ___ / his → ___ / her → ___ / our → ___ / their → ___</div><div class=ei>Fill: Could you ___ / Could I ___ / Could we ___ for 3 polite request situations</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Choose a / an / the / ∅ for 15 sentences covering all four article rules</div><div class=ei>Rewrite 5 sentences replacing possessive adjective + noun with possessive pronoun: "This is my bag." → "This bag is ___."</div><div class=ei>Choose can or could for 6 situations (ability/neutral vs polite request)</div><div class=ei>Write the correct irregular plural in 6 sentences</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 6 sentences — article errors + possessive pronoun errors + irregular plural errors</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your home using all furniture vocabulary + correct articles throughout — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Whose is it? — Identify 5 objects using possessive pronouns correctly</div><div class=ei>Make 4 polite requests using could in a café / shop / classroom context</div><div class=ei>Say 6 irregular plurals in correct sentences immediately on cue</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph describing a place you love — a room, a city, a café, a park (8–10 sentences). Must include: the (×5 — all four rules represented) · a/an (×2) · ∅ no article (×2 — general statements) · a possessive pronoun (×2) · could (×1) · an irregular plural (×2) · furniture or home vocabulary (×3).</div></div></div></div></div></div>
