<div class="unit-block" id="unit-37">
<div class="unit-header">
<div class="unit-num">Unit 37 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div>
<span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span>
<div class="unit-title">There was/were, Must/Mustn&#39;t, Every/Each/Both &amp; Movement</div>
<div class="unit-desc">The final grammar unit before the A1 exam. Six missing CEFR A1 points are formally taught: <em>there was/there were</em> (past existence), <em>must/mustn&#39;t</em> (strong obligation and prohibition), <em>every/each/both</em> (essential determiners), <em>another/other</em> (extremely common at A1), prepositions of movement (into/out of/along/across/through), and adjective collocations (heavy rain/strong wind/high temperature). This completes the A1 grammar syllabus.</div>
<div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:99.5%"></div></div>
</div>
<div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Spiral recycling:</strong> there is/there are (U4) · was/were (U29) · should/have to/need to (U20/U35) · can/can't (U7) · prepositions of place (U7) · directions (U8) · public signs (U35) · adjectives (U4) · ALL prior grammar and vocabulary</span></div>
<div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary — Movement, Collocations &amp; Essential Determiners</div><div class="lesson-sub">Prepositions of movement · Adjective collocations · every/each/both/another/other</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled from All Prior Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">prepositions of place in/on/at/next to (U7)</span><span class="vr">directions turn left/go straight (U8)</span><span class="vr">there is/there are (U4)</span><span class="vr">past simple was/were (U29)</span><span class="vr">must/mustn't preview (public signs U35)</span><span class="vr">adjectives (U4) — now combined as collocations</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">New Vocabulary</div><div class="vgrid"><div class="vi"><div class="vw">into / out of</div><div class="vd">movement: direction towards inside or outside</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">onto / off</div><div class="vd">movement: direction onto a surface or away from it</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">along / across / through / around</div><div class="vd">movement along a path or space</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">towards / away from / past</div><div class="vd">movement in relation to a reference point</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">up / down (the stairs / the hill)</div><div class="vd">movement in vertical direction</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">heavy rain / heavy traffic / heavy bag</div><div class="vd">heavy — not strong or big</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">strong wind / strong coffee / strong accent</div><div class="vd">strong — not heavy or big</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">high temperature / high price / high speed</div><div class="vd">high — not tall for abstract things</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">bad weather / bad traffic / bad cold</div><div class="vd">common bad collocations</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">every day / every week / every morning</div><div class="vd">every + singular noun — all without exception</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">each student / each room / each time</div><div class="vd">each — one by one, individually</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">both sisters / both options / both of them</div><div class="vd">both — two things together</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">another coffee / another day / another chance</div><div class="vd">another — one more, a different one</div></div><div class="vi"><div class="vw">the other one / the other side / other people</div><div class="vd">other — the remaining one(s)</div></div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Movement Mime</div><div class="ad">Students mime an action. Class describes it using a preposition of movement.</div><div class=ap>Student walks across the room → She is walking across the room. / Student runs out of the door → He ran out of the door!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Collocation Match</div><div class="ad">Cards with adjectives and nouns. Students match them correctly — not all adjectives work with all nouns.</div><div class=ap>heavy + rain ✓ / strong + rain ✗ (wrong!) / heavy + wind ✗ / strong + wind ✓ / high + temperature ✓ / big + temperature ✗</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Every / Each / Both / Another / Other — Rapid Choice</div><div class="ad">Teacher gives a sentence frame. Students complete with the correct word immediately.</div><div class=ap>"___ student in the class has a notebook." → Every / Each / "___ my sisters speak French." → Both / "Can I have ___ coffee, please?" → another</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar — There was/were · Must/Mustn't · Every/Each/Both · Another/Other · Prepositions of Movement</div><div class="lesson-sub">Past of there is/are · Strong obligation/prohibition · Determiners · Movement prepositions</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Recycled</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">there is/there are (U4)</span><span class="vr">was/were (U29)</span><span class="vr">should/have to/need to (U20/U35)</span><span class="vr">can/can't (U7)</span><span class="vr">prepositions of place (U7)</span><span class="vr">public signs (U35)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">There was / There were — past of there is/are</div><div class="ge">Parallel to there is/there are (U4) but for past situations. Was = singular. Were = plural.</div><div class="ex">There was a beautiful park near my old house. (singular)</div><div class="ex">There were three bedrooms in my first flat. (plural)</div><div class="ex">Was there a garden? — Yes, there was. / No, there wasn't.</div><div class="ex">Were there any shops nearby? — Yes, there were. / No, there weren't.</div><div class="ex">There wasn't a supermarket in my village — we had to drive 20 kilometres!</div><div class="ex">Ten years ago there were no smartphones. There was only one internet café in town.</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Must / Mustn't — strong obligation and prohibition</div><div class="ge">Must = strong obligation (internal — I feel I must / it is a rule). Mustn't = strong prohibition (forbidden). Different from don't have to (no obligation but allowed).</div><div class="ex">You must show your passport at the border. (external rule)</div><div class="ex">I must call my mother — it's her birthday! (internal feeling)</div><div class="ex">You mustn't smoke in here. (forbidden — like No Smoking sign)</div><div class="ex">You mustn't use your phone during the exam.</div><div class="ex">KEY CONTRAST: You don't have to wear a tie. (not required but allowed)</div><div class="ex">You mustn't wear shoes inside. (forbidden — not allowed)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Every / Each / Both</div><div class="ge">Every = all members of a group (general). Each = every individual one by one. Both = exactly two things together.</div><div class="ex">Every student needs a notebook. (all students, general rule)</div><div class="ex">Each student received a certificate. (one by one, individually)</div><div class="ex">Both my parents are teachers. (exactly two — my mother AND my father)</div><div class="ex">I exercise every day. / She checks her email every morning.</div><div class="ex">Each room has a window. / Both options are good.</div><div class="ex">Every vs Each: often interchangeable but each = more individual focus</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Another / Other / Others</div><div class="ge">Another = one more of the same + singular. Other = different/remaining + plural. The other = the specific remaining one.</div><div class="ex">Could I have another coffee, please? (one more)</div><div class="ex">I don't like this one — can I try another? (a different one)</div><div class="ex">Some students passed; others didn't. (the rest, general)</div><div class="ex">I have two sisters. One is a doctor; the other is a teacher. (the specific remaining one)</div><div class="ex">There are other ways to learn. (different ways, plural)</div></div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">Prepositions of Movement</div><div class="ge">These describe direction of movement — different from prepositions of place which describe position.</div><div class="ex">She walked into the room. (entering — movement)</div><div class="ex">He ran out of the building. (leaving — movement)</div><div class="ex">The cat jumped onto the table. / The cat jumped off the table.</div><div class="ex">We walked along the river for an hour.</div><div class="ex">She swam across the lake.</div><div class="ex">He drove through the tunnel.</div><div class="ex">Walk around the park — don't cut across it!</div><div class="ex">She walked towards me and smiled. / He ran away from the dog.</div></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Practice</div><div class="act"><div class="an">There was/were Time Machine</div><div class="ad">Students describe a place in the past using there was/there were, contrasting with there is/there are now.</div><div class=ap>10 years ago there was a small café on this corner. There were no big shops. There wasn't a metro station — there were only buses. Now there is a huge shopping centre and there are three coffee chains. There isn't a single independent shop left!</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Must or Mustn't or Don't have to?</div><div class="ad">12 situations. Students choose the correct modal.</div><div class=ap>It is forbidden to park here → You mustn't park here. / It is not necessary to book in advance → You don't have to book. / It is very important that you arrive on time → You must arrive on time.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Movement Story</div><div class="ad">Students narrate a journey using at least 6 different prepositions of movement.</div><div class=ap>I walked out of my flat, down the stairs and along the street. I went through the park and across the bridge. I walked towards the station but then I ran past it by mistake!</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — Complete A1 Grammar in Action</div><div class="lesson-sub">Full A1 spiral · there was/were · must/mustn't · every/each/both · another/other · movement prepositions · all prior grammar</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full Active Bank — All 37 Units</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">there was/were</span><span class="vr">must/mustn't</span><span class="vr">every/each/both</span><span class="vr">another/other</span><span class="vr">prepositions of movement into/out of/along/across/through/towards</span><span class="vr">adjective collocations heavy/strong/high/bad</span><span class="vr">the / a / an / ∅ (U36)</span><span class="vr">possessive pronouns (U36)</span><span class="vr">could (U36)</span><span class="vr">ALL prior grammar: to be · have got · present simple · present continuous</span><span class="vr">past simple · going to · can · should · have to · need to · would like</span><span class="vr">let's · comparatives · superlatives · connectors · ordinals · verb+infinitive</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">My Old Neighbourhood</div><div class="ad">Students describe a place from their past using there was/were + now there is/are. Forces natural past/present contrast with all prior grammar.</div><div class=ap>"When I was a child there was a big garden behind my house. There were three apple trees and a small pond. There weren't any houses on our street — it was very quiet. Now there is a new housing development. There are fifty new flats. There isn't a single tree left. Every time I go back I feel sad. It must be very different for the children who live there now."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Museum Rules</div><div class="ad">Students create rules for an imaginary museum using must/mustn't + you can/can't + you have to/don't have to.</div><div class=ap>"You must show your ticket at the door. You mustn't touch the paintings. You can take photos but you mustn't use a flash. Every visitor must be quiet in the galleries. You don't have to buy a guide — there are free maps at the entrance. Each room has information in five languages."</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Journey Story</div><div class="ad">Students tell a story about a real or imaginary journey using all prepositions of movement + past simple + there was/were.</div><div class=ap>"I walked out of the hotel and along the beach. The weather was terrible — there was heavy rain and a strong wind. I ran across the road and into a small café. There were only a few people inside. I ordered another coffee and waited. Both options were bad: go back into the rain or wait forever. I chose another coffee."</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With &amp; Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: A place that no longer exists — there was/were as memory · Full A1 revision</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">A place that no longer exists — a home, a school, a café, a neighbourhood. What was there? What is there now?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "Name one thing that existed in your life 10 years ago but doesn't exist now. Use there was/there were." — past existence language activated in 60 seconds with real personal content.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Describe a place from your past. There was… There were… It was… Every morning I… Both my parents… "There was a small bookshop on my street. Every Saturday morning I went there. Both the owners knew my name. There was always heavy rain in autumn but I went anyway. Now there is a mobile phone shop. I must go back one day."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher collects there was/were errors (confusion with it was/they were), must vs have to vs should, and movement preposition errors (into vs in, out of vs from). Boards all corrections.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Fluency challenge 3 min — FINAL GRAMMAR CHALLENGE:</strong> "Tell me about a place that was important to you — what was there, what you did there, how you got there, what it must have meant to you. Use every grammar point you know. Do not stop."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; Complete A1 grammar active: there was/were + must/mustn't + every/each/both + another/other + movement prepositions + adjective collocations + all 36 prior units. Teacher does final personalised grammar audit for each student.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Exam — Unit 37 Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">Cumulative: Units 1–37 · Final grammar check before A1 exam</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Exam</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Fill: heavy / strong / high / bad for 8 noun collocations</div><div class=ei>Choose the correct preposition of movement for 8 sentences: into/out of/along/across/through/towards/around/past</div><div class=ei>Choose: every / each / both / another / other for 8 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write there was or there were for 6 past descriptions</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Choose must / mustn't / don't have to / don't need to for 8 situations</div><div class=ei>Write there was/were questions and negative sentences for 5 situations</div><div class=ei>Complete 6 sentences with the correct preposition of movement</div><div class=ei>Choose every/each/both/another/other — 8 sentences with context clues</div><div class=ei>Error correction: 6 sentences mixing all new grammar points</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (10 marks)</div><div class=ei>Describe your childhood home or neighbourhood using there was/were — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Give 5 museum/school rules using must/mustn't/don't have to</div><div class=ei>Narrate a short journey using 5 different prepositions of movement — 90 sec</div><div class=ei>Use every/both/another/other correctly in 4 spontaneous sentences</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (10 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a paragraph about a place from your past — a home, school, street or town (8–10 sentences). Must include: there was/there were (×3) · wasn't/weren't (×1) · must or mustn't (×1) · every or each (×1) · both or another (×1) · a preposition of movement (×2) · an adjective collocation heavy/strong/high/bad (×1) · present tense contrast showing how the place has changed.</div></div></div></div></div></div>
