<div class="unit-block" id="unit-35">
<div class="unit-header">
<div class="unit-num">Unit 37 of 37 &#183; A1 Part 2</div>
<span class="part-badge part2-badge">&#128311; Part 2 — Full A1</span>
<div class="unit-title">&#127891; A1 Final Integration</div>
<div class="unit-desc">The final unit. No new grammar or vocabulary — this is pure activation, consolidation and examination. All 25 A1 grammar points, all vocabulary domains from all 37 units, and all 4 skills are tested in the comprehensive A1 final exam. The written portfolio piece and speaking assessment together form the A1 completion certificate and A2 placement tool.</div>
<div class="prog-wrap"><div class="prog-fill" style="width:100%"></div></div>
</div>
<div class="recycle-bar">&#9851;&#65039;&nbsp;<span><strong>Everything active:</strong> ALL 25 grammar points · ALL vocabulary domains · ALL 4 skills · to be · there is/are/was/were · have got · a/an/the/&#8709; · pronouns (subject/object/possessive adjectives &amp; pronouns) · present simple · present continuous · past simple · going to · can/could/should/must/have to/need to/would like · comparatives · superlatives · quantifiers · every/each/both/another/other · connectors · prepositions of place/time/movement · ordinals · irregular plurals · collocations</span></div>
<div class="lessons"><div class="lesson L1"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">1</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Vocabulary Review — All 37 Units</div><div class="lesson-sub">Every vocabulary domain active · No new words · Pure activation and consolidation</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">All Active Vocabulary Domains</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">Greetings · politeness · classroom language (U1/U13)</span><span class="vr">Numbers 1–100 · ordinals 1st–31st · alphabet (U2/U30)</span><span class="vr">Family · physical appearance · feelings (U3/U12/U21)</span><span class="vr">Home · rooms · furniture · objects (U4/U24/U36)</span><span class="vr">Daily routine · time · weather (U5/U19)</span><span class="vr">Food · drink · taste · cooking · recipes (U6/U34)</span><span class="vr">Places in town · public signs · services (U7/U35)</span><span class="vr">Transport · directions · movement prepositions (U8/U37)</span><span class="vr">Shopping · prices · clothes · colours (U9/U10)</span><span class="vr">Countries · nationalities · languages (U11)</span><span class="vr">Jobs · workplaces · technology (U18/U22)</span><span class="vr">Hobbies · sports · seasons · nature · animals (U14/U21/U23)</span><span class="vr">Body · health · illness (U20)</span><span class="vr">Dates · months · occasions · invitations (U30/U31/U32)</span><span class="vr">Quantities · collocations heavy/strong/high (U33/U37)</span><span class="vr">Every · each · both · another · other (U37)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Activation Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Vocabulary Sprint</div><div class="ad">In 3 minutes students write as many words as possible from 5 random topic areas. Then check — are they spelling correctly? Are any words still passive?</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Topic Web Challenge</div><div class="ad">Students connect 10 vocabulary items across 5 different topic areas in a single spoken paragraph. Every word must be used in a correct sentence.</div><div class=ap>My grandmother is an elderly woman with grey hair and brown eyes. She lives in a cosy old flat in the centre of a small Italian town. Every morning she goes to the market to buy fresh vegetables and a little fruit. There is always heavy rain in winter but she walks along the river anyway. Both her daughters live abroad.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Collocation Check</div><div class="ad">15 adjective-noun pairs — students say which are correct collocations and which are wrong. Covers all collocation types from the full course.</div><div class=ap>heavy rain ✓ / strong rain ✗ / high temperature ✓ / big temperature ✗ / bad weather ✓ / ugly weather ✗</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L2"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">2</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Grammar Review — Complete A1 Grammar System</div><div class="lesson-sub">All 25 grammar points · Discrimination tasks · Error correction across all units</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Complete A1 Grammar Inventory</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">to be am/is/are · was/were (U1/U29)</span><span class="vr">there is/are · there was/were (U4/U37)</span><span class="vr">have got (U3) · have for illness (U20)</span><span class="vr">a/an · the · zero article (U2/U36)</span><span class="vr">subject pronouns · object pronouns (U1/U17)</span><span class="vr">possessive adjectives · possessive pronouns · possessive 's (U3/U36)</span><span class="vr">demonstratives this/that/these/those · one/ones (U9/U33)</span><span class="vr">plural nouns regular · irregular plurals (U2/U36)</span><span class="vr">present simple · present continuous (U5/U19)</span><span class="vr">going to · present continuous for future (U22)</span><span class="vr">simple past regular · irregular · was/were (U28/U29)</span><span class="vr">imperatives positive/negative (U13)</span><span class="vr">can/can't · could (U7/U36)</span><span class="vr">should/shouldn't (U20)</span><span class="vr">must/mustn't · have to/don't have to · need to (U35/U37)</span><span class="vr">would like to · want/plan/hope/try + infinitive (U9/U35)</span><span class="vr">like/love/enjoy/hate + -ing (U22)</span><span class="vr">comparatives · superlatives · as…as (U20/U24/U25)</span><span class="vr">quantifiers: some/any/a lot of/a few/a little/too/enough (U6/U33)</span><span class="vr">every/each/both/another/other (U37)</span><span class="vr">Wh- questions · How + adjective · yes/no questions (U2/U26)</span><span class="vr">frequency adverbs · adverbs of manner · intensifiers (U5/U22/U17)</span><span class="vr">prepositions of place · time · movement (U7/U15/U37)</span><span class="vr">connectors and/but/or/so/because/although/first/then (U16)</span><span class="vr">so do I · neither do I (U23)</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Grammar Review Activities</div><div class="gbox"><div class="gr">25-Way Grammar Discrimination Task</div><div class="ge">Students must identify which grammar rule applies in each sentence from the full A1 inventory.</div><div class="ex">She ___ (is/has got/there is) very long hair. → has got</div><div class="ex">___ (A/The/∅) coffee I ordered is cold. → The</div><div class="ex">You ___ (mustn't/don't have to/shouldn't) park here — it's forbidden. → mustn't</div><div class="ex">There ___ (is/was/were) three cinemas in my neighbourhood 20 years ago. → were</div><div class="ex">___ (Every/Both/Each) of my sisters speaks French. → Both</div><div class="ex">She walked ___ (into/in/to) the room and sat down. → into</div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Error Hospital — All 37 Units</div><div class="act"><div class="an">Mega Error Correction</div><div class="ad">25 sentences — one error each. Every A1 grammar point represented. Students correct and name the rule.</div><div class="ap">"She go to work every day." → goes (present simple 3rd person) / "There was a lot of peoples in the park." → people (irregular plural) / "I seen that film last week." → saw (irregular past) / "The life is short." → Life (zero article — general statement) / "Both my sister is a doctor." → Both my sisters are (plural + to be) / "I walked in the building." → into (movement preposition) / "You must to study." → must study (modal + base verb, no to) / "This bag is my." → mine (possessive pronoun, not adjective)</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L3"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">3</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Speaking — The Complete A1 Portrait</div><div class="lesson-sub">All 37 units active simultaneously · Longest sustained speaking task of the level</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Full A1 Active Bank</div><div class="vrrow"><span class="vr">EVERY grammar point from all 37 units</span><span class="vr">EVERY vocabulary domain from all 37 units</span><span class="vr">All tenses: present simple · continuous · past simple · going to</span><span class="vr">All modals: can · could · should · must · have to · need to · would like</span><span class="vr">All articles: a/an · the · zero</span><span class="vr">All pronouns: subject · object · possessive adjectives · pronouns</span><span class="vr">All connectors · comparatives · superlatives · questions · quantifiers</span></div></div><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Speaking Activities</div><div class="act"><div class="an">The Complete Self-Portrait — 5 minutes</div><div class="ad">The most demanding speaking task of the A1 level. Students speak continuously for 5 minutes about themselves — integrating every grammar point and every vocabulary domain. Teacher tracks which grammar points appear and which are still passive.</div><div class=ap>Cover: who you are (nationality/age/appearance) · your family · your home (past and present) · your daily routine · your food · your city · how you get around · what you buy · what you wear · your hobbies · your job · your feelings · your plans · your past · a special occasion · a recipe you know · the rules in your life · something you have too much of · something there used to be in your life that no longer exists.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Grammar Point Roulette</div><div class="ad">Teacher calls out a grammar point at random. Student must produce 2 correct sentences using it within 10 seconds. Covers all 25 grammar points in rapid succession.</div></div><div class="act"><div class="an">Partner Audit</div><div class="ad">Students listen to their partner's 5-minute portrait and note: which grammar points were used correctly? Which were missing or wrong? Give feedback using specific examples.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L4"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">4</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">Spoken + Revision — My Life With &amp; Without</div><div class="lesson-sub">Topic: Your life before this language and your life now · Complete A1 oral exam rehearsal</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">Spoken Club</div><div class="sbox"><div class="sc">&#9878;&#65039; MY LIFE WITH &amp; WITHOUT — Spoken Course</div><div class="st">Your life before this language and your life now — what has changed, what can you do, what are you going to do?</div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">1</div><span><strong>Warm-up:</strong> "In 60 seconds, use as many different grammar points as possible in one continuous speech about yourself." Teacher counts grammar points used. The record is the target to beat.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">2</div><span><strong>Main conversation:</strong> Think about who you were before you started learning this language and who you are now. What was there in your life that is different now? What could you not do before that you can do now? What must you still improve? What are you going to do with this language? "Before I started I couldn't read a menu in English. There was no English in my life at all. Now I can hold a conversation. I must still work on my grammar but I am going to keep practising every day."</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">3</div><span><strong>Language in action:</strong> Teacher conducts the final personalised grammar audit for each student. Identifies remaining gaps. Produces a written note for each student: strong points, points to consolidate at A2.</span></div><div class="sstep"><div class="sn">4</div><span><strong>Final fluency challenge — 5 minutes — no stopping:</strong> "Tell me everything about yourself, your life and your world. Use every grammar point you have learned. Use words from every topic. Do not stop. This is your A1 moment."</span></div><div class="rnote">&#128204; COMPLETE A1 grammar and vocabulary audit. Every grammar point from all 37 units active. Teacher produces personalised A2 readiness report for each student.</div></div></div></div></div><div class="lesson L5"><div class="lesson-header" onclick="tog(this)"><div class="lesson-num">5</div><div style="flex:1"><div class="lesson-title">&#127891; A1 Final Exam — Complete Assessment</div><div class="lesson-sub">All 37 units · All 25 grammar points · All vocabulary domains · 100 marks</div></div><div class="lesson-arrow">&#9660;</div></div><div class="lesson-body"><div class="ls"><div class="ls-title">A1 Final Exam — 100 marks total</div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part A — Vocabulary (25 marks)</div><div class=ei>Mixed labelling: 15 items across all vocabulary domains — family/home/food/clothes/places/transport/body/jobs/animals/technology from pictures</div><div class=ei>Write all 12 months and 7 days of the week from memory</div><div class=ei>Write ordinals for: 1st / 3rd / 8th / 12th / 20th / 21st / 31st</div><div class=ei>Adjective collocations: fill heavy / strong / high / bad for 8 noun phrases</div><div class=ei>Choose every / each / both / another / other / another for 8 sentences</div><div class=ei>Write the correct irregular plural: man / child / foot / tooth / mouse / person / leaf / knife</div><div class=ei>Write possessive pronouns: my→ / your→ / his→ / her→ / our→ / their→</div><div class=ei>Write 6 cooking verbs and 4 kitchen items from pictures</div><div class=ei>Match 8 public signs to their meaning using must/mustn't/you can/you have to</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part B — Grammar (25 marks)</div><div class=ei>25-way discrimination: choose the correct grammar form across all A1 grammar points — 1 sentence per point</div><div class=ei>Article task: fill a / an / the / ∅ in a 10-sentence paragraph — all four rules represented</div><div class=ei>Write questions for 10 given answers using different question types (Wh- / yes-no / how + adjective)</div><div class=ei>Complete 5 sentences using there was/there were — positive, negative, question</div><div class=ei>Modal verb task: choose must / mustn't / should / can / could / have to / don't have to / need to for 8 situations</div><div class=ei>Write 5 sentences in the simple past — mix of regular and irregular verbs</div><div class=ei>Quantifier task: fill some/any/a few/a little/a lot of/too much/too many/not enough for 8 sentences</div><div class=ei>Prepositions task: fill prepositions of place/time/movement for 10 sentences</div><div class=ei>Mega error correction: 10 sentences, one error each, covering all 37 units — student must correct and name the rule</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part C — Speaking (25 marks)</div><div class=ei>Self-portrait: introduce yourself — name, age, nationality, appearance, family, home — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Past story: describe your life or a place using there was/were + past simple — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Future plans: what you are going to do + suggestions using let's + would you like to — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Opinions and comparisons: compare two things using comparatives/superlatives/as…as — 2 min</div><div class=ei>Situation tasks (3 mini role-plays): order food in a café using could / give directions using prepositions of movement / invite and decline using would you like to + I'm afraid — 3 min</div><div class=ei>Final free speech: "Tell me about a place that was important to you — what was there, what you did there, why it mattered." — 4 min using all grammar integrated</div></div><div class="epart"><div class="el">Part D — Writing (25 marks)</div><div class="ed">Write a personal essay of 20–25 sentences covering: who you are · your family · your home (past and present using there was/were) · your daily routine · your city · your plans · a recipe you know · a celebration that is important to you. Every sentence must be grammatically complete. Must include: to be (×3) · there was/were (×2) · present simple (×4) · present continuous (×1) · past simple (×3) · going to (×2) · a modal verb: must/should/can/could/have to (×2) · the definite article correctly (×3) · zero article correctly (×2) · a possessive pronoun (×1) · a comparative or superlative (×1) · a connector: although/because/so/first/then/finally (×2) · a quantifier: a few/a little/too much/not enough (×2) · every/each/both or another/other (×1) · a preposition of movement (×1) · an adjective collocation (×1). This essay is kept in the student's portfolio as evidence of A1 completion and used for A2 placement.</div></div></div></div></div></div>
